{"title_page": "Concha Buika", "text_new": "{{short description|Spanish singer (born 1972)}}\n{{multiple issues|{{BLP sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{too short|date=January 2020}}}}\n{{Spanish name|Balboa|Buika}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Concha Buika\n|image = Concha Buika..JPG\n|caption = Buika in 2013\n|landscape = \n|background = solo_singer\n|birth_name = Mar\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n Balboa Buika\n|alias =Buika\n|origin = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|05|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Palma de Mallorca]], Spain\n|instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]]\n|genre = [[Flamenco]]<br />[[Copla (music)|Copla]]<br />[[Soul music|Soul]]<br />[[Jazz]]|\noccupation = [[Musician]]\n|years_active = 2000\u2013present\n|label = [[Warner Music Group|Warner]]\n|associated_acts = \n|website = {{URL|http://www.conchabuikamusic.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Mar\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n Balboa Buika''' (born 11 May 1972), known as '''Concha Buika''' or '''Buika''', is a [[Spain|Spanish]] singer. Her album ''[[Ni\u00f1a de Fuego]]'' was nominated for the 2008 [[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year]] and ''La Noche M\u00e1s Larga'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Jazz Album|Best Latin Jazz Album]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2014.\n\n==Biography==\nConcha Buika was born on 11 May 1972, in [[Palma de Mallorca]] in Spain.<ref name=Arcos>{{cite news|last1=Arcos|first1=Betto|title=Spanish Singer Buika Awakens From Her Long Night|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/08/31/214509223/spanish-singer-buika-awakens-from-her-long-night|publisher=NPR|accessdate=June 22, 2015|date=August 31, 2013}}</ref> She is the daughter of [[Equatoguinean]] parents, the late writer [[Juan Balboa Boneke|Juan Balboa]] and Honorina Buika. Her brother Guillermo \"Guillem\" Balboa was also born in Equatorial Guinea and he is the current [[alcalde]] of [[Alar\u00f3]], her brother Bore Buika an actor whom has been working in various TV series, such as A\u00edda, El Secreto de Puente Viejo and Anclados, and in movies like ''[[Palmeras en la nieve]]'', ''[[Villaviciosa de al lado]]'' and ''[[Se\u00f1or, dame paciencia]]''. Armando Buika another of her siblings is also an actor \"Stop Over in Hell\" movie and TV series 'Aguila Roja'. Her brother Guillem and her parents were political exiles of their native [[Equatorial Guinea]] and arrived to Spain in 1969, three years before Buika's birth. She currently lives in [[Miami, Florida]], United States.\n\nBuika is a singer, poet, composer and music producer.  Her music draws on a wide range of influences, from jazz and flamenco to pop, soul and African polyrhythm. She began her career as a drummer and bassist, turning to singing only because \"in Spain nobody wanted a female drummer, and I got tired of hearing no, no, no.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rohter|first1=Larry|title=A Singer From Everywhere Arrives Here|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/22/arts/music/22buika.html|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Buika then gained fame singing [[Copla (music)|coplas]] in Madrid nightclubs in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gladstone|first1=Valerie|title=Buika, Genre-Busting Artist, Plays Berlin|url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/buika-genre-busting-artist-plays-berlin/|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 22, 2015|date=April 25, 2010}}</ref> She has been compared to [[Nina Simone]], [[Chavela Vargas]], [[Cesaria Evora]], [[Billie Holiday]], [[Edith Piaf]], and [[Amy Winehouse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Flamenco Sensation Buika Embraces Her Animal Voice|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/06/13/191306990/flamenco-sensation-buika-embraces-her-animal-voice|accessdate=June 22, 2015|publisher=NPR|date=June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Smallman>{{cite news|last1=Smallman|first1=Etan|title=Concha Buika: the outspoken queen of flamenco fusion|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/09/concha-buika-outspoken-queen-flamenco-fusion|work=The Guardian|accessdate=June 22, 2015|date=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Buika released her first album ''Mestizuo'' (2000, Producciones Blau S.L.). This was followed by ''Buika'' (2005, DRO) and a trilogy produced by music producer [[Javier Lim\u00f3n]]: ''Mi Ni\u00f1a Lola'' (My Girl Lola - 2006, DRO), ''Ni\u00f1a de Fuego'' (Girl of Fire - 2008, Warner), which included her first book of poems, and ''El Ultimo Trago'' (The Last Sip - 2009, Warner), an anthology album featuring [[Chucho Vald\u00e9s]], Cuba's standard-bearing pianist, and songs associated with Chavela Vargas, the Mexican ranchera singer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ratliff|first1=Ben|title=BUIKA Y CHUCHO|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/19/arts/music/19choi.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=October 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBuika's largely self-produced seventh album, ''La Noche Mas Larga'' (Warner), recorded in [[New York City]] and [[Madrid]], came out on June 4, 2013.<ref>Bar\u00f3, Carlos Olivares, [http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?page=columnista&id_article=178732 \"La noche m\u00e1s larga de Buika\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701003123/http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?page=columnista&id_article=178732 |date=2013-07-01 }}, ''La Raz\u00f3n'', June 29, 2013.</ref><ref>Spencer, Neil, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jun/23/buika-noche-mas-larga-review \"Buika: La Noche M\u00e1s Larga \u2013 review\"], ''The Observer'', June 23, 2013.</ref> The album contains five of her own compositions, including a collaboration with [[Pat Metheny]] on Buika's own composition \"No Lo Se\", as well as her take on such classic songs as \"La Nave del Olvido\", \"[[Don't Explain (song)|Don't Explain]]\", \"[[Ne Me Quitte Pas]]\" and \"[[Siboney (song)|Siboney]]\".\n\nBuika's second book of poems, ''A Los Que Amaron a Mujeres Dificiles y Acabaron por Soltarse'' (\"To those who loved difficult women and ended up letting go\"), came out through Edaf (Madrid) in the fall of 2014.  She continues to work on producing her first movie based on one of her poems, which is titled \"From Solitude to Hell\".<ref name=Arcos /> Buika is also working on a novel, an opera and an exhibit featuring her photography and her son's artwork.<ref>{{cite news|title=Entrevista con Buika: 'Si he cambiado en algo es en que antes no confiaba en el mundo y ahora s\u00ed'|url=http://www.eliberico.com/entrevista-con-buika-si-he-cambiado-en-algo-es-en-que-antes-no-confiaba-en-el-mundo-y-ahora-si.html|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=El Iberico|date=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2015, her eighth album, ''Vivir Sin Miedo'', was released, the first album containing her own compositions sung in English, Spanish and a mix of the two languages. ''Vivir Sin Miedo'' was recorded over four months in Miami, New York, London and Madrid, co-produced with producer Martin Terefe.<ref name=Smallman /> The first track, also titled \"Vivir Sin Miedo\", was released through all digital channels on July 31, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hildebrand|first1=Lee|title=Singer Buika draws upon a world of influences|url=http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/Singer-Buika-draws-upon-a-world-of-influences-5039734.php|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=SF Gate|date=December 8, 2013}}</ref> The album contains a number of collaborations, including with [[Me'shell Ndegeocello]] and [[Jason Mraz]].\n\nBuika has collaborated with musicians, music producers, Djs and singers in Spanish, Catalan, English, French and Portuguese, with artists such as [[Seal (musician)|Seal]], [[Nelly Furtado]], [[Anoushka Shankar]], [[Chick Corea]], [[Pat Metheny]], [[Nitin Sawhney]], [[Charles Aznavour]], [[Jason Mraz]], [[Martin Terefe]], [[Apparatjik]], [[Ni\u00f1o Josele]], [[Mariza]], [[Bebo Valdes|Bebo]] and [[Chucho Valdes]], [[Luz Casal]], Ivan \"Melon\" Lewis, \"Dizzy\" Daniel Moorehead, [[Jose Luis Perales]], [[Armando Manzanero]], and [[Javier Limon]] amongst others.<ref>{{cite news|last1=\u00c1lvarez|first1=Marcela|title=Buika: 'La m\u00fasica esthe como Dios, est\u00e1 en todas partes'|url=http://www.eldiariony.com/buika-la-musica-es-como-dios-esta-en-todas-partes|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=El Diario|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In 2019 Buika collaborated with [[Carlos Santana]], performing the single \"Los Invisibles\" in [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]] language.\n\nBuika has also collaborated on the soundtracks of several films. In 2011, director [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]] included two Buika songs--\"Por el amor de amar\" (For love's sake) and \"Se me hizo facil\" (I found it easy)--in his movie ''[[La piel que habito]]'' (''The Skin I Live In''). Buika also appeared onscreen for the movie.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gilbert|first1=Andrew|title=Genre-defying diva Buika\u2019s naked ambition|url=http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/Genre-defying-diva-Buika-s-naked-ambition-6088185.php|work=SF Gate|date=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBuika can be heard in the 2010 Angelina Jolie Shiseido Pasion Commercial.\n\nBuika has performed all over the globe, including the United States, Latin America, Japan, most of Europe, the Balkans, Australia, New Zealand, Turkey, Africa, Argentina and Mexico in the last 12 months alone. She has sometimes toured with a small ensemble, usually with  guitar, bass guitar, trombone and [[caj\u00f3n]], as featured on the Buika Para Mi World tour 2017, or with a large orchestra with up to 52 orchestra musicians and 4 Jazz musicians 'Buika Symphonic Experience' where classical music meets Jazz, encouraging all classical musicians to improvise and creating an amazing experience to the audience.\n\nThe Opera, Day of the Dead was a collaborative performance by Apparatjik, Buika and Void at Festspillene i Bergen 2016. Through a series of real time generated audio-, midi- and motion-reactive layered projections, a unique visual narrative was created to accompany the band's performance. This one  '<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stampone|first1=David R.|title=Smoky-voiced Buika brings 'a little bit of everything' to the time event was created as an interactive experiment, investigating strategies for creating a full length opera celebrating the life and death of the artist Julia Pastrana. Perelman|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/music/20140408_Smoky-voiced_Buika_brings__a_little_bit_of_everything__to_the_Perelman.html|accessdate=June 22, 2015|publisher=Philly.com|date=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''[[Buika (album)|Buika]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Mi Ni\u00f1a Lola]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Ni\u00f1a de Fuego]]'' (2008)\n*''[[La Noche M\u00e1s Larga]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Vivir Sin Miedo]]'' (2015)\n*''Para m\u00ed'' (2017)\n'''Collaborations'''\n*''Mestiz\u00fco'' (with Jacob Sureda, 2000)\n*''[[El \u00daltimo Trago]]'' (with [[Chucho Vald\u00e9s]], 2009)\n*''[[Africa Speaks (Santana album)|Africa Speaks]]'' (with [[Santana (band)|Santana]], 2019)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\nBuika's albums have received the following awards:\n* Disco de Oro - certified Gold for the album ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola'', presented by Joaquin Sabina.\n* Best Spanish Song Album: ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola'' (Premios de la Musica, 2007 ).\n* Best Producer: ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola'', Javier Limon (Premios de la Musica, 2007 ).\n* Germany Visual Critics Award 2007: ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola''\n* Disco de Oro - certified gold for ''El Ultimo Trago'' (Colombia, 2010 ).\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2010: Best Traditional Tropical Album for ''El Ultimo Trago''.\n* Luna del Auditorio Nacional Mexico 2013: Best World Music Act '' La Noche m\u00e1s Larga''\n* Antonio-Carlos-Jobim Award Montreal 2017: World Music/ Jazz Cultural crossover.\nBuika's albums and songs have received the following nominations:\n\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2008: Album of the Year: ''Ni\u00f1a de Fuego'' (2008, Warner/Casa Limon ).\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2010: Record of the Year: ''Se Me Hizo Facil''.\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2013: Record of the Year: ''La Nave del Olvido''.\n* Grammy Awards 2013: Best Latin Jazz Album: ''La Noche Mas Larga'' (2013, Warner Music Spain S.L.).\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2016: Record of the Year: ''Si Volver\u00e9''.\n* Grammy Awards 2018: Best World Music Album: Para Mi (2017, Warner Music Spain S.L.).\n\n==See also==\n* [[Glossary of flamenco terms]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Concha Buika}}\n*[http://www.conchabuikamusic.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buika, Concha}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Palma de Mallorca]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Bubi descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Equatoguinean descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish female singers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Spain]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Balearic singers]]\n[[Category:Warner Music Latina artists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Spanish singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Spanish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Spanish-language singers]]\n[[Category:Catalan-language singers]]\n[[Category:English-language singers from Spain]]\n[[Category:French-language singers]]\n[[Category:Portuguese-language singers]]\n[[Category:Yoruba-language singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Spanish singer (born 1972)}}\n{{multiple issues|{{BLP sources|date=May 2012}}\n{{too short|date=January 2020}}}}\n{{Spanish name|Balboa|Buika}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n|name = Concha Buika\n|image = Concha Buika..JPG\n|caption = Buika in 2013\n|landscape = \n|background = solo_singer\n|birth_name = Mar\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n Balboa Buika\n|alias =Buika\n|origin = \n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1972|05|11|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Palma de Mallorca]], Spain\n|instrument = [[Singing|Vocals]]\n|genre = [[Flamenco]]<br />[[Copla (music)|Copla]]<br />[[Soul music|Soul]]<br />[[Jazz]]|\noccupation = [[Musician]]\n|years_active = 2000\u2013present\n|label = [[Warner Music Group|Warner]]\n|associated_acts = \n|website = {{URL|http://www.conchabuikamusic.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Mar\u00eda Concepci\u00f3n Balboa Buika''' (born 11 May 1972), known as '''Concha Buika''' or '''Buika''', is a [[Spain|Spanish]] singer. Her album ''[[Ni\u00f1a de Fuego]]'' was nominated for the 2008 [[Latin Grammy Award for Album of the Year]] and ''La Noche M\u00e1s Larga'' was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Latin Jazz Album|Best Latin Jazz Album]] at the [[56th Annual Grammy Awards]] in 2014.\n\n==Biography==\nConcha Buika was born on 11 May 1972, in [[Palma de Mallorca]] in Spain.<ref name=Arcos>{{cite news|last1=Arcos|first1=Betto|title=Spanish Singer Buika Awakens From Her Long Night|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/08/31/214509223/spanish-singer-buika-awakens-from-her-long-night|publisher=NPR|accessdate=June 22, 2015|date=August 31, 2013}}</ref> She is the daughter of [[Equatoguinean]] parents, the late writer [[Juan Balboa Boneke|Juan Balboa]] and Honorina Buika. Her brother Guillermo \"Guillem\" Balboa was also born in Equatorial Guinea and he is the current [[alcalde]] of [[Alar\u00f3]], her brother Bore Buika an actor whom has been working in various TV series, such as A\u00edda, El Secreto de Puente Viejo and Anclados, and in movies like ''[[Palmeras en la nieve]]'', ''[[Villaviciosa de al lado]]'' and ''[[Se\u00f1or, dame paciencia]]''. Armando Buika another of her siblings is also an actor \"Stop Over in Hell\" movie and TV series 'Aguila Roja'. Her brother Guillem and her parents were political exiles of their native [[Equatorial Guinea]] and arrived to Spain in 1969, three years before Buika's birth. She currently lives in [[Miami, Florida]], United States.\n\nBuika is a singer, poet, composer and music producer.  Her music draws on a wide range of influences, from jazz and flamenco to pop, soul and African polyrhythm. She began her career as a drummer and bassist, turning to singing only because \"in Spain nobody wanted a female drummer, and I got tired of hearing no, no, no.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rohter|first1=Larry|title=A Singer From Everywhere Arrives Here|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/22/arts/music/22buika.html|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=The New York Times}}</ref> Buika then gained fame singing [[Copla (music)|coplas]] in Madrid nightclubs in the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gladstone|first1=Valerie|title=Buika, Genre-Busting Artist, Plays Berlin|url=http://intransit.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/04/25/buika-genre-busting-artist-plays-berlin/|work=The New York Times|accessdate=June 22, 2015|date=April 25, 2010}}</ref> She has been compared to [[Nina Simone]], [[Chavela Vargas]], [[Cesaria Evora]], [[Billie Holiday]], [[Edith Piaf]], and [[Amy Winehouse]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Flamenco Sensation Buika Embraces Her Animal Voice|url=https://www.npr.org/2013/06/13/191306990/flamenco-sensation-buika-embraces-her-animal-voice|accessdate=June 22, 2015|publisher=NPR|date=June 13, 2013}}</ref><ref name=Smallman>{{cite news|last1=Smallman|first1=Etan|title=Concha Buika: the outspoken queen of flamenco fusion|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2015/mar/09/concha-buika-outspoken-queen-flamenco-fusion|work=The Guardian|accessdate=June 22, 2015|date=March 9, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Buika released her first album ''Mestizuo'' (2000, Producciones Blau S.L.). This was followed by ''Buika'' (2005, DRO) and a trilogy produced by music producer [[Javier Lim\u00f3n]]: ''Mi Ni\u00f1a Lola'' (My Girl Lola - 2006, DRO), ''Ni\u00f1a de Fuego'' (Girl of Fire - 2008, Warner), which included her first book of poems, and ''El Ultimo Trago'' (The Last Sip - 2009, Warner), an anthology album featuring [[Chucho Vald\u00e9s]], Cuba's standard-bearing pianist, and songs associated with Chavela Vargas, the Mexican ranchera singer.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ratliff|first1=Ben|title=BUIKA Y CHUCHO|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/19/arts/music/19choi.html?pagewanted=all|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=The New York Times|date=October 18, 2009}}</ref>\n\nBuika's largely self-produced seventh album, ''La Noche Mas Larga'' (Warner), recorded in [[New York City]] and [[Madrid]], came out on June 4, 2013.<ref>Bar\u00f3, Carlos Olivares, [http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?page=columnista&id_article=178732 \"La noche m\u00e1s larga de Buika\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701003123/http://www.razon.com.mx/spip.php?page=columnista&id_article=178732 |date=2013-07-01 }}, ''La Raz\u00f3n'', June 29, 2013.</ref><ref>Spencer, Neil, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/jun/23/buika-noche-mas-larga-review \"Buika: La Noche M\u00e1s Larga \u2013 review\"], ''The Observer'', June 23, 2013.</ref> The album contains five of her own compositions, including a collaboration with [[Pat Metheny]] on Buika's own composition \"No Lo Se\", as well as her take on such classic songs as \"La Nave del Olvido\", \"[[Don't Explain (song)|Don't Explain]]\", \"[[Ne Me Quitte Pas]]\" and \"[[Siboney (song)|Siboney]]\".\n\nBuika's second book of poems, ''A Los Que Amaron a Mujeres Dificiles y Acabaron por Soltarse'' (\"To those who loved difficult women and ended up letting go\"), came out through Edaf (Madrid) in the fall of 2014.  She continues to work on producing her first movie based on one of her poems, which is titled \"From Solitude to Hell\".<ref name=Arcos /> Buika is also working on a novel, an opera and an exhibit featuring her photography and her son's artwork.<ref>{{cite news|title=Entrevista con Buika: 'Si he cambiado en algo es en que antes no confiaba en el mundo y ahora s\u00ed'|url=http://www.eliberico.com/entrevista-con-buika-si-he-cambiado-en-algo-es-en-que-antes-no-confiaba-en-el-mundo-y-ahora-si.html|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=El Iberico|date=April 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2015, her eighth album, ''Vivir Sin Miedo'', was released, the first album containing her own compositions sung in English, Spanish and a mix of the two languages. ''Vivir Sin Miedo'' was recorded over four months in Miami, New York, London and Madrid, co-produced with producer Martin Terefe.<ref name=Smallman /> The first track, also titled \"Vivir Sin Miedo\", was released through all digital channels on July 31, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hildebrand|first1=Lee|title=Singer Buika draws upon a world of influences|url=http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/Singer-Buika-draws-upon-a-world-of-influences-5039734.php|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=SF Gate|date=December 8, 2013}}</ref> The album contains a number of collaborations, including with [[Me'shell Ndegeocello]] and [[Jason Mraz]].\n\nBuika has collaborated with musicians, music producers, Djs and singers in Spanish, Catalan, English, French and Portuguese, with artists such as [[Seal (musician)|Seal]], [[Nelly Furtado]], [[Anoushka Shankar]], [[Chick Corea]], [[Pat Metheny]], [[Nitin Sawhney]], [[Charles Aznavour]], [[Jason Mraz]], [[Martin Terefe]], [[Apparatjik]], [[Ni\u00f1o Josele]], [[Mariza]], [[Bebo Valdes|Bebo]] and [[Chucho Valdes]], [[Luz Casal]], Ivan \"Melon\" Lewis, \"Dizzy\" Daniel Moorehead, [[Jose Luis Perales]], [[Armando Manzanero]], and [[Javier Limon]] amongst others.<ref>{{cite news|last1=\u00c1lvarez|first1=Marcela|title=Buika: 'La m\u00fasica esthe como Dios, est\u00e1 en todas partes'|url=http://www.eldiariony.com/buika-la-musica-es-como-dios-esta-en-todas-partes|accessdate=June 22, 2015|work=El Diario|date=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In 2019 Buika collaborated with [[Carlos Santana]], performing the single \"Los Invisibles\" in [[Yoruba language|Yoruba]] language.\n\nBuika has also collaborated on the soundtracks of several films. In 2011, director [[Pedro Almod\u00f3var]] included two Buika songs--\"Por el amor de amar\" (For love's sake) and \"Se me hizo facil\" (I found it easy)--in his movie ''[[La piel que habito]]'' (''The Skin I Live In''). Buika also appeared onscreen for the movie.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gilbert|first1=Andrew|title=Genre-defying diva Buika\u2019s naked ambition|url=http://www.sfgate.com/music/article/Genre-defying-diva-Buika-s-naked-ambition-6088185.php|work=SF Gate|date=February 20, 2015}}</ref>\n\nBuika can be heard in the 2010 Angelina Jolie Shiseido Pasion Commercial.\n\nBuika has performed all over the globe, including the United States, Latin America, Japan, most of Europe, the Balkans, Australia, New Zealand, Turkey, Africa, Argentina and Mexico in the last 12 months alone. She has sometimes toured with a small ensemble, usually with  guitar, bass guitar, trombone and [[caj\u00f3n]], as featured on the Buika Para Mi World tour 2017, or with a large orchestra with up to 52 orchestra musicians and 4 Jazz musicians 'Buika Symphonic Experience' where classical music meets Jazz, encouraging all classical musicians to improvise and creating an amazing experience to the audience.\n\nThe Opera, Day of the Dead was a collaborative performance by Apparatjik, Buika and Void at Festspillene i Bergen 2016. Through a series of real time generated audio-, midi- and motion-reactive layered projections, a unique visual narrative was created to accompany the band's performance. This one  '<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stampone|first1=David R.|title=Smoky-voiced Buika brings 'a little bit of everything' to the time event was created as an interactive experiment, investigating strategies for creating a full length opera celebrating the life and death of the artist Julia Pastrana. Perelman|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/entertainment/music/20140408_Smoky-voiced_Buika_brings__a_little_bit_of_everything__to_the_Perelman.html|accessdate=June 22, 2015|publisher=Philly.com|date=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n*''[[Buika (album)|Buika]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Mi Ni\u00f1a Lola]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Ni\u00f1a de Fuego]]'' (2008)\n*''[[La Noche M\u00e1s Larga]]'' (2013)\n*''[[Vivir Sin Miedo]]'' (2015)\n*''Para m\u00ed'' (2017)\n'''Collaborations'''\n*''Mestiz\u00fco'' (with Jacob Sureda, 2000)\n*''[[El \u00daltimo Trago]]'' (with [[Chucho Vald\u00e9s]], 2009)\n*''[[Africa Speaks (Santana album)|Africa Speaks]]'' (with [[Santana (band)|Santana]], 2019)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n\nBuika's albums have received the following awards:\n* Disco de Oro - certified Gold for the album ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola'', presented by Joaquin Sabina.\n* Best Spanish Song Album: ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola'' (Premios de la Musica, 2007 ).\n* Best Producer: ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola'', Javier Limon (Premios de la Musica, 2007 ).\n* Germany Visual Critics Award 2007: ''Mi ni\u00f1a Lola''\n* Disco de Oro - certified gold for ''El Ultimo Trago'' (Colombia, 2010 ).\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2010: Best Traditional Tropical Album for ''El Ultimo Trago''.\n* Luna del Auditorio Nacional Mexico 2013: Best World Music Act '' La Noche m\u00e1s Larga''\n* Antonio-Carlos-Jobim Award Montreal 2017: World Music/ Jazz Cultural crossover.\nBuika's albums and songs have received the following nominations:\n\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2008: Album of the Year: ''Ni\u00f1a de Fuego'' (2008, Warner/Casa Limon ).\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2010: Record of the Year: ''Se Me Hizo Facil''.\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2013: Record of the Year: ''La Nave del Olvido''.\n* Grammy Awards 2013: Best Latin Jazz Album: ''La Noche Mas Larga'' (2013, Warner Music Spain S.L.).\n* Latin Grammy Awards 2016: Record of the Year: ''Si Volver\u00e9''.\n* Grammy Awards 2018: Best World Music Album: Para Mi (2017, Warner Music Spain S.L.).\n\n==See also==\n* [[Glossary of flamenco terms]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Concha Buika}}\n*[http://www.conchabuikamusic.com/ Official Website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Buika, Concha}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Palma de Mallorca]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Bubi descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish people of Equatoguinean descent]]\n[[Category:Spanish female singers]]\n[[Category:Bisexual musicians]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from Spain]]\n[[Category:Latin Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Balearic singers]