ennial celebration of the French Revolution.\n|-\n| 1989\n| [[Gaspard Monge]]\n|\n| Buried at the time of the bicentennial celebration of the French Revolution.\n|-\n| 1989\n| [[Marquis de Condorcet]]\n|\n| Buried at the time of the bicentennial celebration of the French Revolution. The coffin is in fact empty, his remains having been lost.\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[Pierre Curie]] Nobel Prize Winner (1903)\n| [[File:Mogila-Pyera-Kyuri.jpg|100px|left]] \n| Enshrined in the crypt in April with his wife and fellow physicist Marie Curie.\n|-\n| 1995\n| [[Marie Curie|Marie Sk\u0142odowska Curie]] Nobel Prize Winner (1903 and 1911)\n| [[File:Pierre & Marie Curie.jpg|100px|left]] \n| Second woman to be buried in the Panth\u00e9on, but the first to be honoured on her own merit.\n|-\n| 1996\n|[[Andr\u00e9 Malraux]]\n|\n| Ashes transferred from Verri\u00e8res-le-Buisson (Essonne) Cemetery on 23 November 1996 on the 20th anniversary of his death.\n|-\n|1998\n|[[Toussaint Louverture]]\n|\n| Commemorative plaque installed on same day as Louis Delgr\u00e8s\n|-\n|1998\n|[[Louis Delgr\u00e8s]]\n|\n| Commemorative plaque installed on same day as Toussaint Louverture\n|-\n| 2002\n| [[Alexandre Dumas, p\u00e8re]]\n|\n| Reburied here 132 years after his death.\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire]]\n|\n| Commemorative plaque installed 6 April 2011; C\u00e9saire is buried in [[Martinique]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://us.franceguide.com/Aime-Cesaire-joins-Voltaire-and-Rousseau-at-the-Pantheon-in-Paris.html?NodeID=1&EditoID=232794 |title=Aim\u00e9 C\u00e9saire joins Voltaire and Rousseau at the Panth\u00e9on in Paris |author=France Guide |year=2011 |publisher=French Government Tourist Office |accessdate=2011-04-09 |quote= }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Jean Zay]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Pierre Brossolette]]\n|\n|\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Germaine Tillion]]\n|\n| Symbolic interment. The coffin of Germaine Tillion at the Panth\u00e9on does not contain her remains but soil from her gravesite, because her family did not want the body itself moved.<ref name=\"news.yahoo.com\">{{cite web |url=https://news.yahoo.com/paris-celebrates-wwii-resistance-heroes-pantheon-ceremony-151542446.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-01-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305112114/http://news.yahoo.com/paris-celebrates-wwii-resistance-heroes-pantheon-ceremony-151542446.html |archivedate=2016-03-05 }}</ref>\n|-\n| 2015\n| [[Genevi\u00e8ve de Gaulle-Anthonioz]]\n|\n| Symbolic interment. The coffin of Genevi\u00e8ve de Gaulle-Anthonioz at the Panth\u00e9on does not contain her remains but soil from her gravesite, because her family did not want the body itself moved.<ref name=\"news.yahoo.com\"/>\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Simone Veil]]\n|\n| Originally buried at [[Montparnasse Cemetery]] following her death in 2017.<ref name=\"en.rfi.fr\">{{Cite news |last1=Roe |first1=David |title=France buries women's rights icon Simone Veil |work=en.rfi.fr |date=2017-07-05 |url=http://en.rfi.fr/france/20170705-france-buries-womens-rights-icon-simone-veil}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smithsonianmag.com/smart-news/simone-veil-will-become-fifth-woman-buried-pantheon-180963947|title=France's Simone Veil Will Become the Fifth Woman Buried in the Panth\u00e9on|first=Brigit|last=Katz|publisher=|accessdate=7 July 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2018\n| [[Antoine Veil]]\n|\n| Husband of Simone Veil, originally buried at Montparnasse Cemetery following his death in 2013.<ref name=\"en.rfi.fr\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Pantheon, Rome]]\n* [[Pante\u00f3n Nacional]], [[Caracas]]\n* [[Pantheon, Moscow]]\n* [[Church of Santa Engr\u00e1cia]], [[Lisbon]]\n* ''[[The Apotheosis of Washington]]''&nbsp;\u2013 dome fresco of the US Capitol\n* [[Listing of the work of Jean Antoine Injalbert-French sculptor]] Sculptor of statue of Mirabeau.\n* [[History of early modern period domes]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Lebeurre|first=Alexia|title=The Pantheon: Temple of the Nation|publisher=\u00c9ditions du Patrimoine|location=Paris|language=English|date=2000|isbn=978-2-858-223435|url=https://archive.org/details/pantheontempleof0000lebe}}\n*{{Cite book|ref=harv|last=Oudin|first=Bernard|title=Dictionnaire des Architectes|language=French|publisher=Seghers|date=1994|ISBN=2-232-10398-6}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Panth\u00e9on de Paris|Panth\u00e9on, Paris}}\n* [http://pantheon.monuments-nationaux.fr/en/ Panth\u00e9on] at Centre des Monuments Nationaux\n* [http://paris1900.lartnouveau.com/paris05/le_pantheon.htm Panth\u00e9on] - current photographs and of the years 1900\n** [http://hal-enpc.archives-ouvertes.fr/docs/00/81/72/87/PDF/BocquetPantheon1992.pdf Panth\u00e9on ou \u00e9glise Sainte-Genevi\u00e8ve? Les ambigu\u00eft\u00e9s d'un monument], Denis Bocquet, MA Thesis, Sorbonne University 1992 \n* {{Structurae|id=20004102|title=Panth\u00e9on}}\n\n{{Visitor attractions in Paris}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pantheon}}\n[[Category:1790 establishments in France]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in the 5th arrondissement of Paris]]\n[[Category:Cemeteries in Paris]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1790]]\n[[Category:Domes]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Paris]]\n[[Category:Monuments historiques of Paris]]\n[[Category:Monuments of the Centre des monuments nationaux]]\n[[Category:Terminating vistas in Paris]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Paris]]\n", "name_user": "Drone Better", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected grammar, made remains part consistent.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Panth%C3%A9on"}
{"title_page": "Junior doctor", "text_new": "{{about|the medical professional designation in the UK|junior doctors in Ireland|Non-consultant hospital doctor|the television series|Junior Doctors: Your Life in Their Hands}}\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], '''junior doctors''' are qualified [[medical practitioner]]s working whilst engaged in postgraduate training. The period of being a junior doctor starts when they qualify as a medical practitioner following graduation with a [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] degree and start the UK [[Foundation Programme]], it culminates in a post as a [[Consultant (medicine)|Consultant]], a [[General Practitioner]] (GP), or some other non-training post, such as a [[Staff grade]] or Associate Specialist post.\n\nThe term ''junior doctor'' currently incorporates the grades of [[Foundation doctor]] and [[Specialty registrar]]. Prior to 2007 it included the grades of [[Pre-registration house officer]], [[Senior house officer]] and [[Specialist registrar]].  During this time junior doctors will do postgraduate examinations to become members of a [[Medical royal college]] relevant to the specialty in which they are training, for example [[Membership of the Royal College of Physicians]] for doctors specialising in [[Internal medicine]], [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons]] for doctors specialising in [[surgery]] or [[Membership of the Royal College of General Practitioners]] for doctors specialising in [[family medicine]].  Doctors typically may be junior doctors for 5\u201315 years, and this may be extended by doing research towards a higher degree, for example towards a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] or [[Doctor of Medicine#UK, Ireland and some Commonwealth countries|Doctor of Medicine]] degree. In England there are around 53,000 junior doctors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/sep/29/junior-doctors-contract-row-nhs-explainer-health |title=Junior doctors contract row: an explainer |first=Denis |last=Campbell |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Working hours==\nIn Europe and the US there has been some reduction of the working hours of doctors who are in postgraduate training, in line with recommendations and legislation aimed at improving patient safety and doctors\u2019 working conditions.<ref name=\"BMJ working hours review\">{{cite journal |journal=[[BMJ]] |title=Impact of reduction in working hours for doctors in training on postgraduate medical education and patients' outcomes: systematic review |first=S R |last=Moonesinghe |volume=342 |doi=10.1136/bmj.d1580 |pmid=21427046 |date=22 March 2011 |pages=d1580}}</ref> In 1991 the government, the [[National Health Service|NHS]] and the [[British Medical Association]] (BMA) agreed a package of measures on working hours, pay and conditions which was called the ''New Deal for Junior Doctors''.  The Doctors' duty hours, which were felt to be excessive, were reduced to a maximum average of 56 hours actual work and 72 hours on call duty per week, although the change was not enforced until 1 December 2000.<ref name=\"Guardian 1Feb2001\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2001/feb/01/health.nhsfinance1 |title=Q & A: Junior doctors' pay deal explained |first=Steve |last=Brown |work=The Guardian |date=1 February 2001|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>  The [[Working Time Directive|European Working Time Directive]] (EWTD) sets out minimum health and safety requirements for the organisation of working time. The EWTD required the average [[Workweek|working week]] to fall to 48 hours or less by 2009.<ref name=\"IJS 2012\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fitzgerald JE, Caesar B |title=The European working time directive: A practical review for surgical trainees |journal=International Journal of Surgery |volume=10 |issue=8 |pages=399\u2013403 |year=2012 |pmid=22925631 |doi=10.1016/j.ijsu.2012.08.007}}</ref>\n\nThe shortening of junior doctors' working hours had implications for how training programmes are organised, especially for specialties such as surgery where there was a tradition of maximising the hours of experience.<ref name=\"IJS 2012\"/> Most studies that have looked at a reduction of junior doctors working hours have found either a beneficial or neutral impact in terms of measures of patient safety, clinical outcomes and postgraduate training.<ref name=\"BMJ working hours review\"/>\n\nThe reduction in number of hours worked by junior doctors is one of the factors leading to blurring distinctions between them and other clinical professions such as [[nurse practitioner]]s who also perform complex tasks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/hospital/trespassers-on-medical-ground-29-09-2009/ |title=Trespassers on medical ground? |first=Clare |last=Lomas |work=[[Nursing Times]] |date=29 September 2009 |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Migration==\nAn [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] survey in December 2015 showed that 35.4% of NHS doctors, 34,000, were born abroad compared with 5% in Italy, 10.7% in Germany and 19.5% in France. The UK was the second highest exporter of doctors, second only to Germany, with 17,000 British doctors working in other OECD countries. These figures are for all doctors in the NHS, not just junior doctors.<ref>{{cite news|title=One in three UK doctors born abroad, international research shows.|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/12060516/One-in-three-UK-doctors-born-abroad-international-research-shows..html|accessdate=28 December 2015|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Career Destination Report published by the UK Foundation Programme Office in 2019, an increasing number of UK junior doctors are seeking to take up work abroad <ref>http://www.foundationprogramme.nhs.uk/sites/default/files/2019-01/F2%20Career%20Destinations%20Report_FINAL.pdf</ref><ref>https://planmyf3.com/guides/f2-career-destinations-report-2018-released</ref>. A report by the General Medical Council described a number of \"push\" and \"pull\" factors, including seeking a better work-life balance and wanting to take advantage of other opportunities abroad<ref>https://planmyf3.com/guides/why-do-doctors-take-breaks-from-their-training-a-gmc-report</ref>. Notably most doctors who complete foundation training do eventually return to specialty training in the UK within three years<ref>https://www.gmc-uk.org/-/media/documents/dc11392-training-pathways-report_pdf-75268632.pdf</ref>.\n\n==Modernising medical careers==\nIn 2005 postgraduate medical training was significantly changed in the [[Modernising Medical Careers]] programme. A two-year [[Foundation Programme]] was introduced for newly qualified doctors, the number of years of postgraduate training changed in some specialities, and doctors needed to decide which speciality to follow sooner after graduation.<ref>{{cite journal |pmc=1199009 |title=Foundation programme for newly qualified doctors |first=Richard |last=Hays |journal=BMJ |date=3 September 2005 |volume=331 |number=7515 |pages=465\u2013466 |doi=10.1136/bmj.331.7515.465 |pmid=16141134}}</ref>\n\nThere were later initiatives to engage junior doctors in NHS leadership; junior doctors are seen as essential to the drives to achieve efficiency savings in the NHS since 2010.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Why we cannot afford not to engage junior doctors in NHS leadership |first1=Benjamin |last1=Brown |first2=Yasmin |last2=Ahmed-Little |first3=Emma |last3=Stanton |journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]] |date=March 2012 |volume=105 |issue=3 |pages=105\u2013110 |doi=10.1258/jrsm.2012.110202|pmid=22434809 |pmc=3308637 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 55em; text-align: left; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: larger;\" | [[National Health Service|<span style=\"padding : 0px 1px 1px 1px; background: #007AC3; ; color: white\">'''''NHS'''''</span>]]&nbsp;'''Medical Career Grades''' \n|-\n!\n|colspan=\"2\"| '''Old System'''\n|colspan=\"2\"| '''New System''' (''Modernising Medical Careers'')\n|-\n! Year 1:\n| colspan=\"2\" |[[Pre-registration house officer|Pre-registration House Officer]] (PRHO)\n1 year\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Foundation House Officer|Foundation Programme]]: 2 years\n|- \n! Year 2: \n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Senior house officer|Senior House Officer]] (SHO) a minimum of 2 years, although often more.\n|-\n! Year 3:\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Specialty Registrar (StR)]] in a hospital specialty: 6\u20138 years\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Specialty Registrar (StR)]] in general practice: 3 years \n|-\n! Year 4:\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Specialist registrar|Specialist Registrar]]:       4\u20136 years\n| [[General Practitioner#UK|GP Registrar]]:     1 year\n|- \n! Year 5:\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[General Practitioner#UK|General Practitioner]]\n''total time in training: 4 years''\n|-\n! Years 6-8:\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[General Practitioner#UK|General Practitioner]]\n''total time in training: 5 years''\n|-\n!Year 9:\n| [[Consultant (medicine)|Consultant]]\n''total time in training: minimum 7''\u2014''9 years''\n| [[Consultant (medicine)|Consultant]]\n''total time in training: 8''\u2014''10 years*''\n|-\n!Optional\n|colspan=\"2\"|''Training may be extended by pursuing medical research (usually two-three years), usually with clinical duties as well''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''Training may be extended by obtaining an [[Academic Clinical Fellowship]] for research, or a Clinical Fellowship for sub-specialisation. *due to competition for consultant posts, it may take longer than 8 years to gain Consultant status .''\n|}\n\n==Pay and conditions==\n{{Update section|date=September 2016}}\n{{see also|Income in the United Kingdom}}\nThe NHS Careers web site stated in 2019:<ref name=\"Pay for doctors\">{{cite web |url=https://www.healthcareers.nhs.uk/explore-roles/doctors/pay-doctors |title=Pay for doctors |website=Health Careers|date=2017 |author= |accessdate= 9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|As a doctor in training you\u2019ll earn a basic salary, plus pay for any hours over 40 per week, a 37 per cent enhancement for working nights, a weekend allowance for any work at the weekend, an availability allowance if you are required to be available on-call, and other potential pay premia.\n\nIn Foundation training, you will earn a basic salary of \u00a327,689 (in Foundation Year 1) to \u00a332,050 (in Foundation Year 2).\n\nIf you\u2019re a doctor starting your specialist training in 2019 your basic starting salary will be \u00a337,935 to \u00a348,075.\n}}\n\nThe basic salaries outlined are defined for a contract of 40 hours per week. Salaries are increased proportionally for any extra hours worked on average per week. Any hours outside \"social\" hours, namely 9pm and 7am, are supplemented by a 37% enhanced rate. Weekend duty is paid as a percentage bonus, up to 10% of the basic salary for working alternate (1 in 2) weekends. Other bonuses are also available for being non-resident on-call (being not physically on site, but available to answer calls or come in to hospital if necessary), for recruitment into academia and undersubscribed specialties, and for doctors living and working in London<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/advice/employment/pay/juniors-pay-england|title=BMA - Pay scales for junior doctors in England|website=www.bma.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhsemployers.org/-/media/Employers/Documents/Pay-and-reward/Pay-and-Conditions-Circular-MD-22019.pdf|title=Pay and Conditions Circular (M&D) 2/2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juniordoctorfinance.co.uk/pay-calculator/|title=Pay calculator|website=Personal Finance for Junior Doctors|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>. In 2015 [[NHS Employers]] reported the total annual earnings for foundation doctors in England averaged just over \u00a336,000. While the basic starting salary for doctors in speciality training was \u00a330,002, NHS Employers were reporting that average earnings in this group of doctors was nearly \u00a353,000.<ref name=\"bbcjan2016\">{{cite news|date=2016-01-04|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-34775980|title=Junior doctors row: What you need to know|author=Nick Triggle|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 graduates who had studied medicine or dentistry were the most likely to be employed and had the highest average gross annual pay when compared to graduates who studied other subjects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/articles/graduatesintheuklabourmarket/2013-11-19|title=Graduates in the UK Labour Market: 2013|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|quote=In 2013 those graduates that had an undergraduate degree in medicine or dentistry were the most likely to be employed and had the highest average gross annual pay}}</ref> In 2015, the average starting salary of junior doctors was the third-highest of all graduate starting salaries, after dentistry and chemical engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://university.which.co.uk/advice/career-prospects/top-degree-subjects-for-graduate-starting-salaries|title=Top 10 degree subjects for graduate starting salaries|publisher=[[Which?]]|quote=Medical degrees have, and will no doubt continue to have, some of the best employment outcomes of any degree in terms of salary expectations and long-term prospects.}}</ref> In 2016, it was reported that after 10 years of employment medicine graduates had the highest salary of all degrees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-36028368|title=To earn more, study medicine or economics, says IFS|author=Brian Milligan|publisher=[[BBC News]]|quote=If you want to earn a big salary, you would be advised to study medicine or economics, says a report by the Institute for Fiscal Studies (IFS). Just ten years after graduation, male medical students earned a median wage of \u00a355,000, the research found. Female medical students also became the highest earners, typically making \u00a345,000 a year.}}</ref> Research conducted in December 2014 showed that across a range of other jobs, almost a third of graduate programmes at Britain's best known and leading employers paid starting salaries of more than \u00a335,000; however, 83% of these leading employers reported that they were recruiting for jobs in London where salaries are higher,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highfliers.co.uk/download/2015/graduate_market/GMReport15.pdf |title=The Graduate Market in 2015 |publisher=High Fliers Research |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/11/18/how-does-your-salary-compare-with-the-rest-of-the-country-5511194/|title=How does your salary compare with the rest of the country?|publisher=Metro|date=2015-11-18}}</ref> whereas NHS salaries are set on a nationwide basis, with doctors in London given an additional payment (\u00a32,162 as of 2013) known as [[London weighting]] to compensate for increased cost of living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stfs.org.uk/doctor/banding-amp-salary|title=F1 Pay Scale|publisher=South Thames Foundation School|date=2014-03-31}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007 junior doctors have been receiving below inflation salary rises.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.d3473 |title=How inflation has downsized your pay |first=Helen |last=Jaques |journal=BMJ |department=Careers |volume=342 |pages=d3473 |date=10 June 2011}}</ref> The independent Review Body on Doctors' and Dentists' Remuneration (DDRB) takes evidence from a range of sources and makes recommendations around pay; in 2015 they recommended a 1% pay increase.<ref name=\"DDRB 2015\">{{cite web|url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/412151/DDRB_47332_Accessible.pdf|title = Review Body on Doctors' and Dentists' Remuneration Forty-Third Report 2015: Figure 2.3|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = DDRB}}</ref> In 2005, the average starting earnings (salary plus bonuses) for a medical graduate was \u00a332,086.<ref>{{cite web|date=2005-10-01 |accessdate=2007-08-02 |url=http://www.bma.org.uk/ap.nsf/Content/ddrbev2005~annex1 |title=Memorandum of evidence to the Review Body on Doctors' and Dentists' Remuneration. Annex 1 - A comparison of graduate earnings |publisher=[[British Medical Association]] |quote=Table 3 - Expected earnings for a medical graduate in the first five years post graduation - Year 1 - Weighted average -\u00a332,086 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608010257/http://www.bma.org.uk/ap.nsf/Content/ddrbev2005~annex1 |archivedate=June 8, 2007 }}</ref> In an inflationary environment all wage-earners, including doctors, may find the buying power of their income becomes less; some describe this as a real-terms cut in pay of 15% between 2007-2014.<ref name=\"DDRB 2015\"/> In 2019, the British Medical Association came to an agreement with NHS England to settle for a guaranteed 2% annual pay rise until 2023<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/collective-voice/influence/key-negotiations/terms-and-conditions/junior-doctor-contract-negotiations/agreed-new-contract-deal-for-junior-doctors-in-england|title=BMA - Agreed new contract deal for junior doctors in England|website=www.bma.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>.\n\n===Expenses===\n{{see also|Tuition fees in the United Kingdom}}\nDoctors pay professional annual fees to maintain registration with the [[General Medical Council]] and [[medical indemnity]] cover. Junior doctors also incur costs associated with training courses, preparing for and sitting exams and college membership; training can be associated with \u00a3420-\u00a33,000 of professional fees annually, depending on stage of training and level of income.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.e5939 |title=Dealing with the costs of being a junior doctor |first1=Usman |last1=Ahmed |first2=Shahbaz |last2=Malik |first3=Yasmin |last3=Akram |journal=BMJ |department=Careers |date=12 September 2012 |volume=345 |pages=e5939}}</ref> English students embarking on a medical degree could in 2015 expect to pay \u00a340,000 on university tuition fees alone.<ref name=\"BMJOpen borrowing\">{{cite journal |title=The lifetime cost to English students of borrowing to invest in a medical degree: a gender comparison using data from the Office for National Statistics |first1=Marco G |last1=Ercolani |first2=Ravinder S |last2=Vohra |first3=Fiona |last3=Carmichael |first4=Karanjit |last4=Mangat |first5=Derek |last5=Alderson |journal=[[BMJ Open]] |date=21 April 2015 |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=e007335 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2014-007335|pmid=25900463 |pmc=4420932 }} {{open access}}</ref> Student loans are available to meet these costs, with repayment starting as soon as individuals begin working as a junior doctor.<ref name=\"BMJOpen borrowing\"/> University tuition in Scotland is free for students ordinarily resident in Scotland, and grants and loans are available to help with living costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/UniversitiesColleges/16640/financial-help|title=Financial help for students|publisher=[[Scottish Government]]|quote=Eligible Scottish domiciled students studying full-time in Scotland are not required to pay tuition fees if studying for a first degree or equivalent. Students may also be eligible to apply for an income assessed bursay and student loan to help with living costs from the Student Awards Agency for Scotland (SAAS)}}</ref>\n\nChanges to working patterns of doctors meant there was no longer a requirement for first year junior doctors to be resident, and from 2008 free accommodation was no longer provided by employers.<ref name=\"BBC accommodation\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cornwall/7415474.stm |title=Doctors in accommodation protest |work=BBC News |date=22 May 2008}}</ref> The British Medical Association said that this amounted to a \u00a34,800 annual pay cut for those who might have previously lived at the hospital rather than independently, but the numbers of doctors involved was not clear.<ref name=\"BBC accommodation\"/> [[Ann Keen]], Labour Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Health Services, stated \"The provision of free accommodation for foundation year 1 doctors who are on call at night, is dependent on the contract of employment of the junior doctor, which is for agreement locally. The Junior Doctors Terms and Conditions of Service continue to provide that if a doctor is contractually required to live in hospital accommodation no charges should be made for the accommodation provided.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2008-06-03a.207297.h |title=Written answers: Junior Doctors: Accommodation|publisher=They Work For You|date=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Prospects===\nThe NHS Careers web site states:<ref name=\"Pay for doctors\"/>\n\n{{cquote|\nIf you\u2019re working as a specialty doctor you\u2019ll earn a basic salary of \u00a337,923 to \u00a370,718.\nAs a consultant you'll earn a basic salary of \u00a376,761 to \u00a3103,490 per year. ... You may apply for local and national Clinical Excellence Awards... If you take on extra responsibilities ... you may expect to be paid more.\n\nConsultants can also supplement their salary by working in private practice.\n\nThere are two contractual options for GPs. They can be:\n\n1) independent contractors who are in charge of running their own practices as business either alone or in partnerships. They have autonomy in how services are delivered according to their contract with the Clinical Commissioning Group. In England, these GPs have increasing responsibility for the commissioning of hospital services for the community\n\n2) salaried GPs who are employees of independent contractor practices or directly employed by primary care organisations. The pay range for salaried GPs is \u00a356,525 to \u00a385,298.}}\n\n===Pension scheme===\n{{see also|Pensions in the United Kingdom}}\nJunior doctors may pay into the [[NHS Pension Scheme]] which from April 2015 has been a Career Average Revalued Earnings (CARE) scheme. The 2015 scheme involves paying towards a pension which will be based on the average of a member's pensionable earnings throughout their whole career, with a revaluation of active members benefits in line with the [[Consumer price index]] plus 1.5 per cent per annum.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhsemployers.org/your-workforce/pay-and-reward/pensions/new-2015-scheme |title=2015 NHS Pension Scheme |publisher=NHS Employers |date=1 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sppa.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=43&Itemid=4|title=Changes to the NHS (Scotland) Pension Scheme from April 2015 |publisher=Scottish Public Pensions Agency|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> The 1995/2008 scheme is closed to new entrants.\n\n===Contract dispute in England===\n{{main|Junior doctors contract dispute in England, 2015}}\nSince 2012 [[NHS Employers]] and the BMA had been in negotiation towards a new contract for junior doctors. These talks ran into serious problems when the Secretary of State for Health, [[Jeremy Hunt]], appeared willing to impose items from the Conservative [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 election]] manifesto upon junior doctors in England.<ref name=\"Guardian 4Nov2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/04/jeremy-hunt-i-cannot-negotiate-on-manifesto-promise-of-24-hour-nhs |title=Jeremy Hunt: I cannot negotiate on manifesto promise of 24-hour NHS |first=Patrick |last=Wintour |work=The Guardian |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the 12th of January 2016, Junior Doctors in [[England]] took part in the first [[general strike]] across the NHS, the first such [[industrial action]] in 40 years. Emergency care was still provided.<ref>{{cite web|last=Triggle |first=Nick |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35286343 |title=Junior doctors' strike: Treatments postponed amid walkout - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2016-01-12}}</ref> There have been claims that the [[Medical Director]] of [[NHS England]], Professor Sir [[Bruce Keogh]], has used performance target levels to justify and encourage [[NHS Trusts]] to declare an emergency situation, forcing Junior Doctors to work despite the [[General strike|strike]], a move to which the [[British Medical Association|BMA]] has condemned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/12093916/Striking-doctors-could-be-ordered-back-in-in-move-which-sparks-fury.html |title=Striking doctors could be ordered back in, in move which sparks fury |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2016-01-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Hunt proposed new contracts for junior doctors which would scrap overtime rates for work between 7am and 10pm on every day except Sunday while increasing their basic pay in a move that Hunt said would be cost neutral, a claim the [[British Medical Association|BMA]] say NHS Employers have been unable to support with robust data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/collective-voice/influence/key-negotiations/terms-and-conditions/junior-and-consultant-contract-home/ddrb-recommendations-analysis-for-juniors/junior-doctors-contract-negotiations-faq|title=FAQs on junior doctor contract proposals|work=BMJ|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/oct/17/leader-of-nhs-junior-doctors-urges-jeremy-hunt-to-reopen-negotiations|title=Leader of NHS junior doctors urges Jeremy Hunt to reopen negotiations|author=Denis Campbell|work=the Guardian}}</ref> In response, the doctor's union, the [[British Medical Association|BMA]], called for a strike, the first since the 1970s.<ref name=guardian10102015>{{cite web|title = Junior doctors to be balloted for strike action, says British Medical Association|url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/sep/26/junior-doctors-to-be-balloted-for-strike-action-bma|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 10 October 2015|first = Press|last = Association}}</ref> The strike vote started on 5 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-34591056|title=Junior doctors to vote on strike action - British Medical Association}}</ref> In November 2015, the BMA balloted over 37,700 of their members in response to Hunt's contract proposals; 76% of eligible doctors voted with 99.6% of doctors voting for action short of strike and 98% voting for all out strike.<ref name=\"Guardian 19Nov2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/19/nhs-strikes-junior-doctors-vote-action-bma |title=Junior doctors overwhelmingly vote for NHS strikes |first=Denis |last=Campbell |work=The Guardian |date=19 November 2015 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>  In November 2015 Hunt said he would offer a basic pay increase of 11%, but still removing compensation for longer hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/03/jeremy-hunt-offer-junior-doctors-pay-rise|title=Jeremy Hunt offers junior doctors 11% pay rise in bid to end dispute}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1581227/payrise-offer-a-pr-stunt-say-junior-doctors|title=Payrise Offer A PR Stunt, Say Junior Doctors}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/junior-doctors-claim-jeremy-hunts-11-pay-rise-will-be-a-pay-cut-of-26-a6720476.html|title=Junior doctors claim Jeremy Hunt's 11% pay rise will be a 'pay cut' of 26%}}</ref> On 19 November 2015 the result of the BMA strike ballot was announced, with more than 99% in favour of industrial action short of a strike, and 98% voting for full strike action. Hunt said the strike was \"very disappointing\", but declined the appeal for arbitration at this time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34868934|title=Junior doctors: Jeremy Hunt says strike vote 'very disappointing'}}</ref> He was criticized for failing to answer MP's questions about the strike, with his deputy claiming he was too busy preparing for the strike.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-hunt-an-absolute-disgrace-for-refusing-to-face-mps-questions-on-junior-doctors-strike-a6741931.html|title=Jeremy Hunt an 'absolute disgrace' for refusing to face MPs' questions on junior doctors strike}}</ref> Hunt eventually agreed to discussions overseen by [[Acas]]. After five days of talks between the government and BMA, Hunt withdrew his threat to impose a new contract without agreement and the strike action that had been planned for December was suspended.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/junior-doctors-strike-called-off-a6755091.html |title=Junior doctors strike called off to grant more time for talks |first=Charlie |last=Cooper |work=The Independent |date=1 December 2015|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> The first day of strike action was called off hours before it was due to start (too late to avoid some disruption), with later days suspended.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-34965603|title=Disruption expected as junior doctors' strike called off}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/30/doctors-strike-jeremy-hunt-announces-potential-agreement-with-bma|title=Doctors' strike called off after Hunt lifts threat to impose new contract}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/junior-doctors-strike-called-off-a6755091.html|title=Junior doctors strike called off to grant more time for talks}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 December 2015, Dr [[Johann Malawana]], leader of the BMA\u2019s junior doctors committee (JDC), gave a 4 January deadline for the talks to result an acceptable outcome, or industrial action would be announced.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/dec/29/junior-doctors-implement-strike-action-plans-nhs-government-talks-falter | title=Junior doctors likely to strike as government talks falter}}</ref> An agreement was not reached by this deadline and so the BMA announced that a strike would go ahead, blaming \"the government's continued failure to address junior doctors\u2019 concerns about the need for robust contractual safeguards on safe working, and proper recognition for those working unsocial hours\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/jan/04/junior-doctors-to-strike-next-tuesday-after-talks-with-government-break-down|title=Junior doctors in England to strike next week after talks break down}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/junior-doctors-announce-they-will-strike-next-week-a6796396.html| title=Junior doctors announce they will strike next week}}</ref> The first day of the strike went ahead on 12 January.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/junior-doctors-strike-live-poll-finds-strong-public-support-for-strike-a6807011.html|title=Junior doctors' strike live: Jeremy Hunt brands strike 'unnecessary' as poll shows high public support for stoppage}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35294637|title=Junior doctors' strike: Get back to negotiating table - Hunt}}</ref> Junior doctors again withdrew their labour for routine care on 10 February 2016, leading to the cancellation of around 3,000 elective operations.<ref name=\"BBC 10FebSep2016\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35535704 |work=[[BBC News]] |title='Operations hit as doctors strike again |date=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Rest breaks===\nIn a case involving [[University Hospitals of Derby and Burton NHS Foundation Trust]] in July 2019 the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]] decided that the trust had breached the 2002 contract for junior doctors because their hours and rest periods had been underestimated by commercial software over some years. The case will affect other NHS employers and substantial arrears will be due.<ref>{{cite news |title=Junior doctors win landmark case over rest breaks |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/workforce/junior-doctors-win-landmark-case-over-rest-breaks/7025655.article? |accessdate=3 September 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Patient mortality==\nThe period in August where there was a large changeover of hospital staff has sometimes been dubbed the \"killing season\" (due to a perception that there is an associated rise in the number of patient deaths).<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8269729.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |title='Deaths rise' with junior doctors |date=22 September 2009}}</ref> In 2009 research looking at emergency admissions to hospitals in England established that a small but statistically significant increase in patient mortality was occurring during August.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Early In-Hospital Mortality following Trainee Doctors' First Day at Work |first1=Min Hua |last1=Jen |first2=Alex |last2=Bottle |first3=Azeem |last3=Majeed |first4=Derek |last4=Bell |first5=Paul |last5=Aylin |journal=[[PLoS ONE]] |date=23 September 2009 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0007103 |volume=4 |issue = 9|pages=e7103 |pmid=19774078 |pmc=2743809|bibcode=2009PLoSO...4.7103J }}</ref> The limited data was collected retrospectively over an 8-year period, comparing two week-long blocks (one week prior to commencement, one week post commencement). The methodology meant that drawing firm conclusions was unwise with correlation not implying causation.<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\"/> In the month when junior doctors start working - when other factors are adjusted for patients had a 6% increase in mortality.<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\"/> For patients admitted as an emergency who were not requiring surgery or suffering from cancer, the mortality rate increased by 7.86%.<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\"/>\n\nOther concerns have been raised regarding mortality following admission to hospital at a weekend. A research paper published in 2012, looked retrospectively at data from 2009; the study observed an increase in 30-day mortality for people admitted to hospital on Saturday and Sunday, compared to mid-week days.<ref name=\"JRSM weekend\">{{cite journal |title=Weekend hospitalization and additional risk of death: An analysis of inpatient data |first1=N |last1=Freemantle |first2=M |last2=Richardson |first3=J |last3=Wood |first4=D |last4=Ray |first5=S |last5=Khosla |first6=D |last6=Shahian |first7=WR |last7=Roche |first8=I |last8=Stephens |first9=B |last9=Keogh |first10=D |last10=Pagano |journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine |date=February 2012 |volume=105 |issue=2 |pages=74\u201384 |doi=10.1258/jrsm.2012.120009 |pmid=22307037 |pmc=3284293}}</ref> The risk of dying in a hospital on Saturday or Sunday was actually less than on a weekday.<ref name=\"JRSM weekend\"/> The data in the study did not enable the authors to describe the cause of this so-called [[weekend effect]]. Subsequently, there has been considerable speculation around whether the availability of consultants was a factor.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/18/jeremy-hunt-statement-on-nhs-weekend-hospital-care-is-misleading-experts-warn |title=Jeremy Hunt statement on weekend hospital care is misleading, experts warn |first1=Faye |last1=Kirkland |first2=Denis |last2=Campbell |work=The Guardian |date=19 November 2015}}</ref> The authors of the paper have also openly criticised the conclusions drawn by the government and popular media on the paper, saying that to draw such conclusions as to associated decreased weekend staffing levels to increased mortality at 30 days post-admission would be \"rash and misleading\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/351/bmj.h4596/rapid-responses |title=Increased mortality associated with weekend hospital admission: a case for expanded seven day services? |publisher=The BMJ |date= |accessdate=2016-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Foundation doctor]]\n* [[Specialty registrar]]\n* [[Bullying in medicine]]\n* [[List of health and medical strikes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151123095959/http://www.aomrc.org.uk/doc_view/152-do-you-know-who-is-treating-you-a-patient-s-guide-to-doctors-in-training A patient's guide to doctors in training] by the [[Academy of Medical Royal Colleges|AoMRC]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Junior Doctor}}\n[[Category:Physicians]]\n[[Category:Healthcare occupations in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the medical professional designation in the UK|junior doctors in Ireland|Non-consultant hospital doctor|the television series|Junior Doctors: Your Life in Their Hands}}\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], '''junior doctors''' are qualified [[medical practitioner]]s working whilst engaged in postgraduate training. The period of being a junior doctor starts when they qualify as a medical practitioner following graduation with a [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] degree and start the UK [[Foundation Programme]], it culminates in a post as a [[Consultant (medicine)|Consultant]], a [[General Practitioner]] (GP), or some other non-training post, such as a [[Staff grade]] or Associate Specialist post.\n\nThe term ''junior doctor'' currently incorporates the grades of [[Foundation doctor]] and [[Specialty registrar]]. Prior to 2007 it included the grades of [[Pre-registration house officer]], [[Senior house officer]] and [[Specialist registrar]].  During this time junior doctors will do postgraduate examinations to become members of a [[Medical royal college]] relevant to the specialty in which they are training, for example [[Membership of the Royal College of Physicians]] for doctors specialising in [[Internal medicine]], [[Membership of the Royal College of Surgeons]] for doctors specialising in [[surgery]] or [[Membership of the Royal College of General Practitioners]] for doctors specialising in [[family medicine]].  Doctors typically may be junior doctors for 5\u201315 years, and this may be extended by doing research towards a higher degree, for example towards a [[Doctor of Philosophy]] or [[Doctor of Medicine#UK, Ireland and some Commonwealth countries|Doctor of Medicine]] degree. In England there are around 53,000 junior doctors.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/sep/29/junior-doctors-contract-row-nhs-explainer-health |title=Junior doctors contract row: an explainer |first=Denis |last=Campbell |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Working hours==\nIn Europe and the US there has been some reduction of the working hours of doctors who are in postgraduate training, in line with recommendations and legislation aimed at improving patient safety and doctors\u2019 working conditions.<ref name=\"BMJ working hours review\">{{cite journal |journal=[[BMJ]] |title=Impact of reduction in working hours for doctors in training on postgraduate medical education and patients' outcomes: systematic review |first=S R |last=Moonesinghe |volume=342 |doi=10.1136/bmj.d1580 |pmid=21427046 |date=22 March 2011 |pages=d1580}}</ref> In 1991 the government, the [[National Health Service|NHS]] and the [[British Medical Association]] (BMA) agreed a package of measures on working hours, pay and conditions which was called the ''New Deal for Junior Doctors''.  The Doctors' duty hours, which were felt to be excessive, were reduced to a maximum average of 56 hours actual work and 72 hours on call duty per week, although the change was not enforced until 1 December 2000.<ref name=\"Guardian 1Feb2001\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2001/feb/01/health.nhsfinance1 |title=Q & A: Junior doctors' pay deal explained |first=Steve |last=Brown |work=The Guardian |date=1 February 2001|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>  The [[Working Time Directive|European Working Time Directive]] (EWTD) sets out minimum health and safety requirements for the organisation of working time. The EWTD required the average [[Workweek|working week]] to fall to 48 hours or less by 2009.<ref name=\"IJS 2012\">{{cite journal |vauthors=Fitzgerald JE, Caesar B |title=The European working time directive: A practical review for surgical trainees |journal=International Journal of Surgery |volume=10 |issue=8 |pages=399\u2013403 |year=2012 |pmid=22925631 |doi=10.1016/j.ijsu.2012.08.007}}</ref>\n\nThe shortening of junior doctors' working hours had implications for how training programmes are organised, especially for specialties such as surgery where there was a tradition of maximising the hours of experience.<ref name=\"IJS 2012\"/> Most studies that have looked at a reduction of junior doctors working hours have found either a beneficial or neutral impact in terms of measures of patient safety, clinical outcomes and postgraduate training.<ref name=\"BMJ working hours review\"/>\n\nThe reduction in number of hours worked by junior doctors is one of the factors leading to blurring distinctions between them and other clinical professions such as [[nurse practitioner]]s who also perform complex tasks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nursingtimes.net/news/hospital/trespassers-on-medical-ground-29-09-2009/ |title=Trespassers on medical ground? |first=Clare |last=Lomas |work=[[Nursing Times]] |date=29 September 2009 |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Migration==\nAn [[Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development]] survey in December 2015 showed that 35.4% of NHS doctors, 34,000, were born abroad compared with 5% in Italy, 10.7% in Germany and 19.5% in France. The UK was the second highest exporter of doctors, second only to Germany, with 17,000 British doctors working in other OECD countries. These figures are for all doctors in the NHS, not just junior doctors.<ref>{{cite news|title=One in three UK doctors born abroad, international research shows.|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/12060516/One-in-three-UK-doctors-born-abroad-international-research-shows..html|accessdate=28 December 2015|publisher=Daily Telegraph|date=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Career Destination Report published by the UK Foundation Programme Office in 2019, an increasing number of UK junior doctors are seeking to take up work abroad <ref>http://www.foundationprogramme.nhs.uk/sites/default/files/2019-01/F2%20Career%20Destinations%20Report_FINAL.pdf</ref><ref>https://planmyf3.com/guides/f2-career-destinations-report-2018-released</ref>. A report by the General Medical Council described a number of \"push\" and \"pull\" factors, including seeking a better work-life balance and wanting to take advantage of other opportunities abroad<ref>https://planmyf3.com/guides/why-do-doctors-take-breaks-from-their-training-a-gmc-report</ref>. Notably most doctors who complete foundation training do eventually return to specialty training in the UK within three years<ref>https://www.gmc-uk.org/-/media/documents/dc11392-training-pathways-report_pdf-75268632.pdf</ref>.\n\n==Modernising medical careers==\nIn 2005 postgraduate medical training was significantly changed in the [[Modernising Medical Careers]] programme. A two-year [[Foundation Programme]] was introduced for newly qualified doctors, the number of years of postgraduate training changed in some specialities, and doctors needed to decide which speciality to follow sooner after graduation.<ref>{{cite journal |pmc=1199009 |title=Foundation programme for newly qualified doctors |first=Richard |last=Hays |journal=BMJ |date=3 September 2005 |volume=331 |number=7515 |pages=465\u2013466 |doi=10.1136/bmj.331.7515.465 |pmid=16141134}}</ref>\n\nThere were later initiatives to engage junior doctors in NHS leadership; junior doctors are seen as essential to the drives to achieve efficiency savings in the NHS since 2010.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Why we cannot afford not to engage junior doctors in NHS leadership |first1=Benjamin |last1=Brown |first2=Yasmin |last2=Ahmed-Little |first3=Emma |last3=Stanton |journal=[[Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine]] |date=March 2012 |volume=105 |issue=3 |pages=105\u2013110 |doi=10.1258/jrsm.2012.110202|pmid=22434809 |pmc=3308637 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width: 55em; text-align: left; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ style=\"font-size: larger;\" | [[National Health Service|<span style=\"padding : 0px 1px 1px 1px; background: #007AC3; ; color: white\">'''''NHS'''''</span>]]&nbsp;'''Medical Career Grades''' \n|-\n!\n|colspan=\"2\"| '''Old System'''\n|colspan=\"2\"| '''New System''' (''Modernising Medical Careers'')\n|-\n! Year 1:\n| colspan=\"2\" |[[Pre-registration house officer|Pre-registration House Officer]] (PRHO)\n1 year\n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Foundation House Officer|Foundation Programme]]: 2 years\n|- \n! Year 2: \n| colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | [[Senior house officer|Senior House Officer]] (SHO) a minimum of 2 years, although often more.\n|-\n! Year 3:\n| rowspan=\"4\" | [[Specialty Registrar (StR)]] in a hospital specialty: 6\u20138 years\n| rowspan=\"3\" | [[Specialty Registrar (StR)]] in general practice: 3 years \n|-\n! Year 4:\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Specialist registrar|Specialist Registrar]]:       4\u20136 years\n| [[General Practitioner#UK|GP Registrar]]:     1 year\n|- \n! Year 5:\n| rowspan=\"3\"|[[General Practitioner#UK|General Practitioner]]\n''total time in training: 4 years''\n|-\n! Years 6-8:\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[General Practitioner#UK|General Practitioner]]\n''total time in training: 5 years''\n|-\n!Year 9:\n| [[Consultant (medicine)|Consultant]]\n''total time in training: minimum 7''\u2014''9 years''\n| [[Consultant (medicine)|Consultant]]\n''total time in training: 8''\u2014''10 years*''\n|-\n!Optional\n|colspan=\"2\"|''Training may be extended by pursuing medical research (usually two-three years), usually with clinical duties as well''\n|colspan=\"2\"|''Training may be extended by obtaining an [[Academic Clinical Fellowship]] for research, or a Clinical Fellowship for sub-specialisation. *due to competition for consultant posts, it may take longer than 8 years to gain Consultant status .''\n|}\n\n==Pay and conditions==\n{{Update section|date=September 2016}}\n{{see also|Income in the United Kingdom}}\nThe NHS Careers web site stated in 2019:<ref name=\"Pay for doctors\">{{cite web |url=https://www.healthcareers.nhs.uk/explore-roles/doctors/pay-doctors |title=Pay for doctors |website=Health Careers|date=2017 |author= |accessdate= 9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|As a doctor in training you\u2019ll earn a basic salary, plus pay for any hours over 40 per week, a 37 per cent enhancement for working nights, a weekend allowance for any work at the weekend, an availability allowance if you are required to be available on-call, and other potential pay premia.\n\nIn Foundation training, you will earn a basic salary of \u00a327,689 (in Foundation Year 1) to \u00a332,050 (in Foundation Year 2).\n\nIf you\u2019re a doctor starting your specialist training in 2019 your basic starting salary will be \u00a337,935 to \u00a348,075.\n}}\n\nThe basic salaries outlined are defined for a contract of 40 hours per week. Salaries are increased proportionally for any extra hours worked on average per week. Any hours outside \"social\" hours, namely 9pm and 7am, are supplemented by a 37% enhanced rate. Weekend duty is paid as a percentage bonus, up to 10% of the basic salary for working alternate (1 in 2) weekends. Other bonuses are also available for being non-resident on-call (being not physically on site, but available to answer calls or come in to hospital if necessary), for recruitment into academia and undersubscribed specialties, and for doctors living and working in London<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/advice/employment/pay/juniors-pay-england|title=BMA - Pay scales for junior doctors in England|website=www.bma.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nhsemployers.org/-/media/Employers/Documents/Pay-and-reward/Pay-and-Conditions-Circular-MD-22019.pdf|title=Pay and Conditions Circular (M&D) 2/2019|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juniordoctorfinance.co.uk/pay-calculator/|title=Pay calculator|website=Personal Finance for Junior Doctors|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>. In 2015 [[NHS Employers]] reported the total annual earnings for foundation doctors in England averaged just over \u00a336,000. While the basic starting salary for doctors in speciality training was \u00a330,002, NHS Employers were reporting that average earnings in this group of doctors was nearly \u00a353,000.<ref name=\"bbcjan2016\">{{cite news|date=2016-01-04|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-34775980|title=Junior doctors row: What you need to know|author=Nick Triggle|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 graduates who had studied medicine or dentistry were the most likely to be employed and had the highest average gross annual pay when compared to graduates who studied other subjects.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/employmentandemployeetypes/articles/graduatesintheuklabourmarket/2013-11-19|title=Graduates in the UK Labour Market: 2013|publisher=[[Office for National Statistics]]|quote=In 2013 those graduates that had an undergraduate degree in medicine or dentistry were the most likely to be employed and had the highest average gross annual pay}}</ref> In 2015, the average starting salary of junior doctors was the third-highest of all graduate starting salaries, after dentistry and chemical engineering.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://university.which.co.uk/advice/career-prospects/top-degree-subjects-for-graduate-starting-salaries|title=Top 10 degree subjects for graduate starting salaries|publisher=[[Which?]]|quote=Medical degrees have, and will no doubt continue to have, some of the best employment outcomes of any degree in terms of salary expectations and long-term prospects.}}</ref> In 2016, it was reported that after 10 years of employment medicine graduates had the highest salary of all degrees.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-36028368|title=To earn more, study medicine or economics, says IFS|author=Brian Milligan|publisher=[[BBC News]]|quote=If you want to earn a big salary, you would be advised to study medicine or economics, says a report by the Institute for Fiscal Studies (IFS). Just ten years after graduation, male medical students earned a median wage of \u00a355,000, the research found. Female medical students also became the highest earners, typically making \u00a345,000 a year.}}</ref> Research conducted in December 2014 showed that across a range of other jobs, almost a third of graduate programmes at Britain's best known and leading employers paid starting salaries of more than \u00a335,000; however, 83% of these leading employers reported that they were recruiting for jobs in London where salaries are higher,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.highfliers.co.uk/download/2015/graduate_market/GMReport15.pdf |title=The Graduate Market in 2015 |publisher=High Fliers Research |accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/11/18/how-does-your-salary-compare-with-the-rest-of-the-country-5511194/|title=How does your salary compare with the rest of the country?|publisher=Metro|date=2015-11-18}}</ref> whereas NHS salaries are set on a nationwide basis, with doctors in London given an additional payment (\u00a32,162 as of 2013) known as [[London weighting]] to compensate for increased cost of living.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stfs.org.uk/doctor/banding-amp-salary|title=F1 Pay Scale|publisher=South Thames Foundation School|date=2014-03-31}}</ref>\n\nSince 2007 junior doctors have been receiving below inflation salary rises.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.d3473 |title=How inflation has downsized your pay |first=Helen |last=Jaques |journal=BMJ |department=Careers |volume=342 |pages=d3473 |date=10 June 2011}}</ref> The independent Review Body on Doctors' and Dentists' Remuneration (DDRB) takes evidence from a range of sources and makes recommendations around pay; in 2015 they recommended a 1% pay increase.<ref name=\"DDRB 2015\">{{cite web|url = https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/412151/DDRB_47332_Accessible.pdf|title = Review Body on Doctors' and Dentists' Remuneration Forty-Third Report 2015: Figure 2.3|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = DDRB}}</ref> In 2005, the average starting earnings (salary plus bonuses) for a medical graduate was \u00a332,086.<ref>{{cite web|date=2005-10-01 |accessdate=2007-08-02 |url=http://www.bma.org.uk/ap.nsf/Content/ddrbev2005~annex1 |title=Memorandum of evidence to the Review Body on Doctors' and Dentists' Remuneration. Annex 1 - A comparison of graduate earnings |publisher=[[British Medical Association]] |quote=Table 3 - Expected earnings for a medical graduate in the first five years post graduation - Year 1 - Weighted average -\u00a332,086 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070608010257/http://www.bma.org.uk/ap.nsf/Content/ddrbev2005~annex1 |archivedate=June 8, 2007 }}</ref> In an inflationary environment all wage-earners, including doctors, may find the buying power of their income becomes less; some describe this as a real-terms cut in pay of 15% between 2007-2014.<ref name=\"DDRB 2015\"/> In 2019, the British Medical Association came to an agreement with NHS England to settle for a guaranteed 2% annual pay rise through 2023<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/collective-voice/influence/key-negotiations/terms-and-conditions/junior-doctor-contract-negotiations/agreed-new-contract-deal-for-junior-doctors-in-england|title=BMA - Agreed new contract deal for junior doctors in England|website=www.bma.org.uk|access-date=2019-11-19}}</ref>.\n\n===Expenses===\n{{see also|Tuition fees in the United Kingdom}}\nDoctors pay professional annual fees to maintain registration with the [[General Medical Council]] and [[medical indemnity]] cover. Junior doctors also incur costs associated with training courses, preparing for and sitting exams and college membership; training can be associated with \u00a3420-\u00a33,000 of professional fees annually, depending on stage of training and level of income.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1136/bmj.e5939 |title=Dealing with the costs of being a junior doctor |first1=Usman |last1=Ahmed |first2=Shahbaz |last2=Malik |first3=Yasmin |last3=Akram |journal=BMJ |department=Careers |date=12 September 2012 |volume=345 |pages=e5939}}</ref> English students embarking on a medical degree could in 2015 expect to pay \u00a340,000 on university tuition fees alone.<ref name=\"BMJOpen borrowing\">{{cite journal |title=The lifetime cost to English students of borrowing to invest in a medical degree: a gender comparison using data from the Office for National Statistics |first1=Marco G |last1=Ercolani |first2=Ravinder S |last2=Vohra |first3=Fiona |last3=Carmichael |first4=Karanjit |last4=Mangat |first5=Derek |last5=Alderson |journal=[[BMJ Open]] |date=21 April 2015 |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=e007335 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2014-007335|pmid=25900463 |pmc=4420932 }} {{open access}}</ref> Student loans are available to meet these costs, with repayment starting as soon as individuals begin working as a junior doctor.<ref name=\"BMJOpen borrowing\"/> University tuition in Scotland is free for students ordinarily resident in Scotland, and grants and loans are available to help with living costs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gov.scot/Topics/Education/UniversitiesColleges/16640/financial-help|title=Financial help for students|publisher=[[Scottish Government]]|quote=Eligible Scottish domiciled students studying full-time in Scotland are not required to pay tuition fees if studying for a first degree or equivalent. Students may also be eligible to apply for an income assessed bursay and student loan to help with living costs from the Student Awards Agency for Scotland (SAAS)}}</ref>\n\nChanges to working patterns of doctors meant there was no longer a requirement for first year junior doctors to be resident, and from 2008 free accommodation was no longer provided by employers.<ref name=\"BBC accommodation\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cornwall/7415474.stm |title=Doctors in accommodation protest |work=BBC News |date=22 May 2008}}</ref> The British Medical Association said that this amounted to a \u00a34,800 annual pay cut for those who might have previously lived at the hospital rather than independently, but the numbers of doctors involved was not clear.<ref name=\"BBC accommodation\"/> [[Ann Keen]], Labour Parliamentary Under-Secretary for Health Services, stated \"The provision of free accommodation for foundation year 1 doctors who are on call at night, is dependent on the contract of employment of the junior doctor, which is for agreement locally. The Junior Doctors Terms and Conditions of Service continue to provide that if a doctor is contractually required to live in hospital accommodation no charges should be made for the accommodation provided.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/wrans/?id=2008-06-03a.207297.h |title=Written answers: Junior Doctors: Accommodation|publisher=They Work For You|date=3 June 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Prospects===\nThe NHS Careers web site states:<ref name=\"Pay for doctors\"/>\n\n{{cquote|\nIf you\u2019re working as a specialty doctor you\u2019ll earn a basic salary of \u00a337,923 to \u00a370,718.\nAs a consultant you'll earn a basic salary of \u00a376,761 to \u00a3103,490 per year. ... You may apply for local and national Clinical Excellence Awards... If you take on extra responsibilities ... you may expect to be paid more.\n\nConsultants can also supplement their salary by working in private practice.\n\nThere are two contractual options for GPs. They can be:\n\n1) independent contractors who are in charge of running their own practices as business either alone or in partnerships. They have autonomy in how services are delivered according to their contract with the Clinical Commissioning Group. In England, these GPs have increasing responsibility for the commissioning of hospital services for the community\n\n2) salaried GPs who are employees of independent contractor practices or directly employed by primary care organisations. The pay range for salaried GPs is \u00a356,525 to \u00a385,298.}}\n\n===Pension scheme===\n{{see also|Pensions in the United Kingdom}}\nJunior doctors may pay into the [[NHS Pension Scheme]] which from April 2015 has been a Career Average Revalued Earnings (CARE) scheme. The 2015 scheme involves paying towards a pension which will be based on the average of a member's pensionable earnings throughout their whole career, with a revaluation of active members benefits in line with the [[Consumer price index]] plus 1.5 per cent per annum.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhsemployers.org/your-workforce/pay-and-reward/pensions/new-2015-scheme |title=2015 NHS Pension Scheme |publisher=NHS Employers |date=1 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sppa.gov.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=43&Itemid=4|title=Changes to the NHS (Scotland) Pension Scheme from April 2015 |publisher=Scottish Public Pensions Agency|accessdate=22 November 2015}}</ref> The 1995/2008 scheme is closed to new entrants.\n\n===Contract dispute in England===\n{{main|Junior doctors contract dispute in England, 2015}}\nSince 2012 [[NHS Employers]] and the BMA had been in negotiation towards a new contract for junior doctors. These talks ran into serious problems when the Secretary of State for Health, [[Jeremy Hunt]], appeared willing to impose items from the Conservative [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 election]] manifesto upon junior doctors in England.<ref name=\"Guardian 4Nov2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/04/jeremy-hunt-i-cannot-negotiate-on-manifesto-promise-of-24-hour-nhs |title=Jeremy Hunt: I cannot negotiate on manifesto promise of 24-hour NHS |first=Patrick |last=Wintour |work=The Guardian |date=4 November 2015 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn the 12th of January 2016, Junior Doctors in [[England]] took part in the first [[general strike]] across the NHS, the first such [[industrial action]] in 40 years. Emergency care was still provided.<ref>{{cite web|last=Triggle |first=Nick |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35286343 |title=Junior doctors' strike: Treatments postponed amid walkout - BBC News |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=1970-01-01 |accessdate=2016-01-12}}</ref> There have been claims that the [[Medical Director]] of [[NHS England]], Professor Sir [[Bruce Keogh]], has used performance target levels to justify and encourage [[NHS Trusts]] to declare an emergency situation, forcing Junior Doctors to work despite the [[General strike|strike]], a move to which the [[British Medical Association|BMA]] has condemned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/health/news/12093916/Striking-doctors-could-be-ordered-back-in-in-move-which-sparks-fury.html |title=Striking doctors could be ordered back in, in move which sparks fury |publisher=Telegraph |date= |accessdate=2016-01-12}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2015, Hunt proposed new contracts for junior doctors which would scrap overtime rates for work between 7am and 10pm on every day except Sunday while increasing their basic pay in a move that Hunt said would be cost neutral, a claim the [[British Medical Association|BMA]] say NHS Employers have been unable to support with robust data.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bma.org.uk/collective-voice/influence/key-negotiations/terms-and-conditions/junior-and-consultant-contract-home/ddrb-recommendations-analysis-for-juniors/junior-doctors-contract-negotiations-faq|title=FAQs on junior doctor contract proposals|work=BMJ|accessdate=31 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/oct/17/leader-of-nhs-junior-doctors-urges-jeremy-hunt-to-reopen-negotiations|title=Leader of NHS junior doctors urges Jeremy Hunt to reopen negotiations|author=Denis Campbell|work=the Guardian}}</ref> In response, the doctor's union, the [[British Medical Association|BMA]], called for a strike, the first since the 1970s.<ref name=guardian10102015>{{cite web|title = Junior doctors to be balloted for strike action, says British Medical Association|url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/sep/26/junior-doctors-to-be-balloted-for-strike-action-bma|website = the Guardian|accessdate = 10 October 2015|first = Press|last = Association}}</ref> The strike vote started on 5 November.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-34591056|title=Junior doctors to vote on strike action - British Medical Association}}</ref> In November 2015, the BMA balloted over 37,700 of their members in response to Hunt's contract proposals; 76% of eligible doctors voted with 99.6% of doctors voting for action short of strike and 98% voting for all out strike.<ref name=\"Guardian 19Nov2015\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/19/nhs-strikes-junior-doctors-vote-action-bma |title=Junior doctors overwhelmingly vote for NHS strikes |first=Denis |last=Campbell |work=The Guardian |date=19 November 2015 |accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref>  In November 2015 Hunt said he would offer a basic pay increase of 11%, but still removing compensation for longer hours.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/03/jeremy-hunt-offer-junior-doctors-pay-rise|title=Jeremy Hunt offers junior doctors 11% pay rise in bid to end dispute}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.sky.com/story/1581227/payrise-offer-a-pr-stunt-say-junior-doctors|title=Payrise Offer A PR Stunt, Say Junior Doctors}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/junior-doctors-claim-jeremy-hunts-11-pay-rise-will-be-a-pay-cut-of-26-a6720476.html|title=Junior doctors claim Jeremy Hunt's 11% pay rise will be a 'pay cut' of 26%}}</ref> On 19 November 2015 the result of the BMA strike ballot was announced, with more than 99% in favour of industrial action short of a strike, and 98% voting for full strike action. Hunt said the strike was \"very disappointing\", but declined the appeal for arbitration at this time.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34868934|title=Junior doctors: Jeremy Hunt says strike vote 'very disappointing'}}</ref> He was criticized for failing to answer MP's questions about the strike, with his deputy claiming he was too busy preparing for the strike.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/jeremy-hunt-an-absolute-disgrace-for-refusing-to-face-mps-questions-on-junior-doctors-strike-a6741931.html|title=Jeremy Hunt an 'absolute disgrace' for refusing to face MPs' questions on junior doctors strike}}</ref> Hunt eventually agreed to discussions overseen by [[Acas]]. After five days of talks between the government and BMA, Hunt withdrew his threat to impose a new contract without agreement and the strike action that had been planned for December was suspended.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/junior-doctors-strike-called-off-a6755091.html |title=Junior doctors strike called off to grant more time for talks |first=Charlie |last=Cooper |work=The Independent |date=1 December 2015|accessdate=3 January 2016}}</ref> The first day of strike action was called off hours before it was due to start (too late to avoid some disruption), with later days suspended.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-34965603|title=Disruption expected as junior doctors' strike called off}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2015/nov/30/doctors-strike-jeremy-hunt-announces-potential-agreement-with-bma|title=Doctors' strike called off after Hunt lifts threat to impose new contract}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/health-and-families/health-news/junior-doctors-strike-called-off-a6755091.html|title=Junior doctors strike called off to grant more time for talks}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 December 2015, Dr [[Johann Malawana]], leader of the BMA\u2019s junior doctors committee (JDC), gave a 4 January deadline for the talks to result an acceptable outcome, or industrial action would be announced.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/dec/29/junior-doctors-implement-strike-action-plans-nhs-government-talks-falter | title=Junior doctors likely to strike as government talks falter}}</ref> An agreement was not reached by this deadline and so the BMA announced that a strike would go ahead, blaming \"the government's continued failure to address junior doctors\u2019 concerns about the need for robust contractual safeguards on safe working, and proper recognition for those working unsocial hours\".<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/jan/04/junior-doctors-to-strike-next-tuesday-after-talks-with-government-break-down|title=Junior doctors in England to strike next week after talks break down}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/junior-doctors-announce-they-will-strike-next-week-a6796396.html| title=Junior doctors announce they will strike next week}}</ref> The first day of the strike went ahead on 12 January.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/junior-doctors-strike-live-poll-finds-strong-public-support-for-strike-a6807011.html|title=Junior doctors' strike live: Jeremy Hunt brands strike 'unnecessary' as poll shows high public support for stoppage}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35294637|title=Junior doctors' strike: Get back to negotiating table - Hunt}}</ref> Junior doctors again withdrew their labour for routine care on 10 February 2016, leading to the cancellation of around 3,000 elective operations.<ref name=\"BBC 10FebSep2016\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-35535704 |work=[[BBC News]] |title='Operations hit as doctors strike again |date=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Rest breaks===\nIn a case involving [[University Hospitals of Derby and Burton NHS Foundation Trust]] in July 2019 the [[Court of Appeal (England and Wales)|Court of Appeal]] decided that the trust had breached the 2002 contract for junior doctors because their hours and rest periods had been underestimated by commercial software over some years. The case will affect other NHS employers and substantial arrears will be due.<ref>{{cite news |title=Junior doctors win landmark case over rest breaks |url=https://www.hsj.co.uk/workforce/junior-doctors-win-landmark-case-over-rest-breaks/7025655.article? |accessdate=3 September 2019 |publisher=Health Service Journal |date=31 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Patient mortality==\nThe period in August where there was a large changeover of hospital staff has sometimes been dubbed the \"killing season\" (due to a perception that there is an associated rise in the number of patient deaths).<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\">{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/8269729.stm |work=[[BBC News]] |title='Deaths rise' with junior doctors |date=22 September 2009}}</ref> In 2009 research looking at emergency admissions to hospitals in England established that a small but statistically significant increase in patient mortality was occurring during August.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Early In-Hospital Mortality following Trainee Doctors' First Day at Work |first1=Min Hua |last1=Jen |first2=Alex |last2=Bottle |first3=Azeem |last3=Majeed |first4=Derek |last4=Bell |first5=Paul |last5=Aylin |journal=[[PLoS ONE]] |date=23 September 2009 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0007103 |volume=4 |issue = 9|pages=e7103 |pmid=19774078 |pmc=2743809|bibcode=2009PLoSO...4.7103J }}</ref> The limited data was collected retrospectively over an 8-year period, comparing two week-long blocks (one week prior to commencement, one week post commencement). The methodology meant that drawing firm conclusions was unwise with correlation not implying causation.<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\"/> In the month when junior doctors start working - when other factors are adjusted for patients had a 6% increase in mortality.<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\"/> For patients admitted as an emergency who were not requiring surgery or suffering from cancer, the mortality rate increased by 7.86%.<ref name=\"BBC 22Sep2015\"/>\n\nOther concerns have been raised regarding mortality following admission to hospital at a weekend. A research paper published in 2012, looked retrospectively at data from 2009; the study observed an increase in 30-day mortality for people admitted to hospital on Saturday and Sunday, compared to mid-week days.<ref name=\"JRSM weekend\">{{cite journal |title=Weekend hospitalization and additional risk of death: An analysis of inpatient data |first1=N |last1=Freemantle |first2=M |last2=Richardson |first3=J |last3=Wood |first4=D |last4=Ray |first5=S |last5=Khosla |first6=D |last6=Shahian |first7=WR |last7=Roche |first8=I |last8=Stephens |first9=B |last9=Keogh |first10=D |last10=Pagano |journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine |date=February 2012 |volume=105 |issue=2 |pages=74\u201384 |doi=10.1258/jrsm.2012.120009 |pmid=22307037 |pmc=3284293}}</ref> The risk of dying in a hospital on Saturday or Sunday was actually less than on a weekday.<ref name=\"JRSM weekend\"/> The data in the study did not enable the authors to describe the cause of this so-called [[weekend effect]]. Subsequently, there has been considerable speculation around whether the availability of consultants was a factor.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/18/jeremy-hunt-statement-on-nhs-weekend-hospital-care-is-misleading-experts-warn |title=Jeremy Hunt statement on weekend hospital care is misleading, experts warn |first1=Faye |last1=Kirkland |first2=Denis |last2=Campbell |work=The Guardian |date=19 November 2015}}</ref> The authors of the paper have also openly criticised the conclusions drawn by the government and popular media on the paper, saying that to draw such conclusions as to associated decreased weekend staffing levels to increased mortality at 30 days post-admission would be \"rash and misleading\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmj.com/content/351/bmj.h4596/rapid-responses |title=Increased mortality associated with weekend hospital admission: a case for expanded seven day services? |publisher=The BMJ |date= |accessdate=2016-01-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Foundation doctor]]\n* [[Specialty registrar]]\n* [[Bullying in medicine]]\n* [[List of health and medical strikes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20151123095959/http://www.aomrc.org.uk/doc_view/152-do-you-know-who-is-treating-you-a-patient-s-guide-to-doctors-in-training A patient's guide to doctors in training] by the [[Academy of Medical Royal Colleges|AoMRC]]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Junior Doctor}}\n[[Category:Physicians]]\n[[Category:Healthcare occupations in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "Motorwayman7", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePay and conditions:Remove Americanism", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Junior_doctor"}
{"title_page": "Les amazones", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{M\u00e9hul operas}}\n\n'''''Les amazones, ou La fondation de Th\u00e8bes''''' (''The Amazons, or The Founding of Thebes'') is an opera in three acts by the French composer [[\u00c9tienne M\u00e9hul]] with a [[libretto]] by [[Victor-Joseph \u00c9tienne de Jouy]]. It was first performed at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] on 17 December 1811 with the [[Napoleon I|Emperor Napoleon]] and his new wife, [[Marie-Louise of Austria|Marie-Louise]] in the audience. The plot, which concerns the reconciliation of two warring peoples, was intended to symbolise the peace between France and Austria.<ref>Ad\u00e9la\u00efde de Place, p.140</ref>\n\n==Performance history==\nThe opera was a failure, its lack of success blamed on the weak libretto. M\u00e9hul's early biographer, Pierre Vieillard, was one of the musicians at the premiere. He wrote, \"A bizarre occurrence added to the woes of this sorry work. The worst thing which went wrong was the denouement which, one might say, fell from a great height, since Jupiter himself appeared up in the air to recognise Amphion and Zethus as his sons. At the very moment when this revelation should have stopped short the Amazons, ready to strike down the unknown children of their queen, a cloud chariot was indeed seen to descend from the flies, but no Jupiter; the [[deus ex machina]] was missing. Absorbed in conversation, the actor Bertin had failed to hear the machine operator's whistle, and the chariot left without the god. He had to be restrained from throwing himself from the top of the stage. What made the accident even more heartbreaking for him was that the Emperor Napoleon and Marie-Louise were among the spectators of this disastrous performance. I was in the orchestra and I can bear witness to the hilarity this episode aroused in their Imperial Majesties. I doubt the great Napoleon ever laughed so heartily.\"<ref>Vieillard pp.37-38</ref>\n\nM\u00e9hul, his health already undermined by [[tuberculosis]], was crushed by the failure of ''Les amazones''. [[Elisabeth Bartlet (musicologist)|Elizabeth Bartlet]] describes it as \"the worst blow that the composer ever experienced.\"<ref>Bartlet, p. viii</ref> M\u00e9hul gave up writing for the stage for a while and retired to his house at [[Pantin]] in order to devote himself to his passion for gardening.<ref>Ad\u00e9la\u00efde de Place, p.140</ref>\n\n==Roles==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Role\n!Voice type\n!Premiere Cast, 17 December 1811<br>(Conductor:)\n|-\n|Antiope, ''Queen of the Amazons''\n|[[soprano]]\n|[[Alexandrine-Caroline Branchu]]\t \n|-\n|\u00c9riphile, ''a young Amazon''\n|soprano\n|[[Augustine Albert|Augustine Albert-Hymm]]\t \n|-\n|Amphion\n|[[tenor]]\n|[[Louis Nourrit]]\t \n|-\n|Z\u00e9thus, ''Amphion's brother''\n|[[bass (voice)|bass]]\n|[[Henri-\u00c9tienne D\u00e9rivis]]\t \n|-\n|Jupiter\n|bass\n|Jean-Honor\u00e9 Bertin\t \n|-\n|Licidas, ''the Theban chief'' \n|bass\n|Duparc\n|-\n|An Amazon\n|soprano\n|Jos\u00e9phine Armand\n|-\n|A Theban officer\n|\n|Henrard\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"|''Chorus of warriors, Amazons, Theban people''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Alexandre Dratwicki & Etienne Jardin, ''Le Fer et les Fleurs : Etienne-Nicolas M\u00e9hul (1763-1817)'' (Actes Sud & Palazzetto Bru Zane, 2017)\n*Ad\u00e9la\u00efde de Place ''\u00c9tienne Nicolas M\u00e9hul'' (Bleu Nuit \u00c9diteur, 2005)\n*Pierre Vieillard ''M\u00e9hul: sa vie et ses \u0153uvres'' (Ledoyen, 1859) \n*General introduction to M\u00e9hul's operas in the  introduction to the edition of ''[[Stratonice (opera)|Stratonice]]'' by M. Elizabeth C. Bartlet (Pendragon Press, 1997)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=12Q6AAAAcAAJ&dq=jouy+amazones&source=gbs_navlinks_s Libretto in Jouy's \"Works\" (Google Books)]\n\n{{\u00c9tienne M\u00e9hul|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amazones, Les}}\n\n[[Category:Operas by \u00c9tienne M\u00e9hul]]\n[[Category:1811 operas]]\n[[Category:French-language operas]]\n[[Category:Operas]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{M\u00e9hul operas}}\n\n'''''Les amazones, ou La fondation de Th\u00e8bes''''' (''The Amazons, or The Founding of Thebes'') is an opera in three acts by the French composer [[\u00c9tienne M\u00e9hul]] with a [[libretto]] by [[Victor-Joseph \u00c9tienne de Jouy]]. It was first performed at the [[Paris Op\u00e9ra]] on 17 December 1811 with the [[Napoleon I|Emperor Napoleon]] and his new wife, [[Marie-Louise of Austria|Marie-Louise]] in the audience. The plot, which concerns the reconciliation of two warring peoples, was intended to symbolise the peace between France and Austria.<ref>Ad\u00e9la\u00efde de Place, p.140</ref>\n\n==Performance history==\nThe opera was a failure, its lack of success blamed on the weak libretto. M\u00e9hul's early biographer, Pierre Vieillard, was one of the musicians at the premiere. He wrote, \"A bizarre occurrence added to the woes of this sorry work. The worst thing which went wrong was the denouement which, one might say, fell from a great height, since Jupiter himself appeared up in the air to recognise Amphion and Zethus as his sons. At the very moment when this revelation should have stopped short the Amazons, ready to strike down the unknown children of their queen, a cloud chariot was indeed seen to descend from the flies, but no Jupiter; the [[deus ex machina]] was missing. Absorbed in conversation, the actor Bertin had failed to hear the machine operator's whistle, and the chariot left without the god. He had to be restrained from throwing himself from the top of the stage. What made the accident even more heartbreaking for him was that the Emperor Napoleon and Marie-Louise were among the spectators of this disastrous performance. I was in the orchestra and I can bear witness to the hilarity this episode aroused in their Imperial Majesties. I doubt the great Napoleon ever laughed so heartily.\"<ref>Vieillard pp.37-38</ref>\n\nM\u00e9hul, his health already undermined by [[tuberculosis]], was crushed by the failure of ''Les amazones''. [[Elisabeth Bartlet (musicologist)|Elizabeth Bartlet]] describes it as \"the worst blow that the composer ever experienced.\"<ref>Bartlet, p. viii</ref> M\u00e9hul gave up writing for the stage for a while and retired to his house at [[Pantin]] in order to devote himself to his passion for gardening.<ref>Ad\u00e9la\u00efde de Place, p.140</ref>\n\n==Roles==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Role\n!Voice type\n!Premiere Cast, 17 December 1811<br>(Conductor:)\n|-\n|Antiope, ''Queen of the Amazons''\n|[[soprano]]\n|[[Alexandrine-Caroline Branchu]]\t \n|-\n|\u00c9riphile, ''a young Amazon''\n|soprano\n|[[Augustine Albert|Augustine Albert-Hymm]]\t \n|-\n|Amphion\n|[[tenor]]\n|[[Louis Nourrit]]\t \n|-\n|Z\u00e9thus, ''Amphion's brother''\n|[[bass (voice)|bass]]\n|[[Henri-\u00c9tienne D\u00e9rivis]]\t \n|-\n|Jupiter\n|bass\n|Jean-Honor\u00e9 Bertin\t \n|-\n|Licidas, ''the Theban chief'' \n|bass\n|Duparc\n|-\n|An Amazon\n|soprano\n|Jos\u00e9phine Armand\n|-\n|A Theban officer\n|\n|Henrard\n|-\n| colspan=\"3\"|''Chorus of warriors, Amazons, Theban people''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Ad\u00e9la\u00efde de Place ''\u00c9tienne Nicolas M\u00e9hul'' (Bleu Nuit \u00c9diteur, 2005)\n*Pierre Vieillard ''M\u00e9hul: sa vie et ses \u0153uvres'' (Ledoyen, 1859) \n*General introduction to M\u00e9hul's operas in the  introduction to the edition of ''[[Stratonice (opera)|Stratonice]]'' by M. Elizabeth C. Bartlet (Pendragon Press, 1997)\n\n==External links==\n*[https://books.google.com/books?id=12Q6AAAAcAAJ&dq=jouy+amazones&source=gbs_navlinks_s Libretto in Jouy's \"Works\" (Google Books)]\n\n{{\u00c9tienne M\u00e9hul|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Amazones, Les}}\n\n[[Category:Operas by \u00c9tienne M\u00e9hul]]\n[[Category:1811 operas]]\n[[Category:French-language operas]]\n[[Category:Operas]]\n", "name_user": "Alexandredratwicki", "label": "safe", "comment": "new book reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Les_amazones"}
{"title_page": "Lydia Canaan", "text_new": "{{short description|Lebanese singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2015}}\n{{Use American English|date=May 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Lydia Canaan <br /> \u0644\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627 \u0643\u0646\u0639\u0627\u0646\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = {{!}}border<!-- Please do not change to a different image unless a very specific reason is given for doing so and consensus has been achieved in the talk page. Such image additions will be reverted -->\n| image_size = \n| caption = Lydia Canaan, first rock star of the [[Middle East]]\n| native_name = \u0644\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627 \u0643\u0646\u0639\u0627\u0646\n| birth_name = Lydia Canaan\n| alias = Angel\n| birth_date =<!-- Birth date has been contested. Do not add without providing a reliably published source with a reputation for editorial oversight. -->\n| birth_place = [[Brummana]], [[Lebanon]]\n| occupation = {{hlist |[[List of singer-songwriters#Lebanon|Singer-songwriter]] |[[United Nations|United Nations delegate]]}}\n| instrument = Vocals ([[List of mezzo-sopranos in non-classical music|mezzo-soprano]])\n| years_active = 1984\u2013present\n| label = {{hlist |Pulse-8 |SIDI/XEMA |[[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG/Metro]]}}\n|associated_acts = {{hlist| [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]] | [[Robin Scott (singer)|Robin Scott]] | [[M (band)|M]] | [[Tommy Mandel]] | [[Marco Sabiu]] | [[Barry Blue]] | [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]] | [[The Rapino Brothers]] | [[Keith Barnhart]] }}\n|website = {{URL|lydiacanaan.com}}\n| Genre = {{hlist |Rock |[[pop rock]] |pop}}\n}}\n'''Lydia Canaan''' ({{lang-ar| \u0644\u064a\u062f\u064a\u0627 \u0643\u0646\u0639\u0627\u0646}}) is a [[List of Lebanese people (diaspora)|Lebanese]] singer-songwriter and humanitarian activist widely regarded as the first \u201c[[Superstar|rock star]]\u201d of the Middle East.<ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\">O'Connor, Tom. [https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2016/Apr-27/349450-lydia-canaan-one-step-closer-to-rocknroll-hall-of-fame.ashx \"Lydia Canaan One Step Closer to Rock n' Roll Hall of Fame\"], ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', Beirut, April 27, 2016. Retrieved August 18, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\">Salhani, Justin. \n[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2014/Nov-17/277842-lydia-canaan-the-mideasts-first-rock-star.ashx? \"Lydia Canaan: The Mideast\u2019s First Rock Star\"], ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', Beirut, November 17, 2014. Retrieved August 18, 2017.</ref>\n\nCredited as the first internationally successful Lebanese recording artist,<ref name=\"billboarddec27\">Sinclair, David. \"Global Music Pulse\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', New York, December 27, 1997.</ref><ref name=\"books.google.com.lb\">Sinclair, David. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Kg8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA49 \"Global Music Pulse\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', New York, May 10, 1997.</ref><ref name=\"Edward D'Mello Gulf News\">D'Mello, Edward. \"A Singing Sensation: Unprecedented Success For Lebanese Singer Lydia Canaan\", ''[[Gulf News]]'', Dubai, November 29, 2000.</ref><ref name=\"HayekNo12513\">Hayek, George. \"The Lebanese Singer Lydia Canaan Has Invaded the European Market With Her Ballads\", ''[[Al-Hayat]]'', No. 12,513, Beirut, June 3, 1997.</ref><ref name=\"Khalife2000\">Khalife, Mireille. \"Lydia Canaan Tells Her Story...and Launches Her English Songs Internationally from Lebanon\", ''Al-Hayat'', No. 13,732, Beirut, October 16, 2000.</ref> Canaan rose to [[Celebrity#Regional and cultural implications|fame]] performing [[rock music]] in [[English language|English]] amid enemy military attacks during the [[Lebanese Civil War]],<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\">Chandran, Sudha. \"An Angel's Song\", ''[[The Gulf Today]]'', Sharjah, November 24, 2000.</ref> holding concerts in vicinities of [[Lebanon]] that were simultaneously being bombed.<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\"/> Hala Habib of ''Society'' wrote, \u201cin a small country that was ripped by war, there was this young girl making a difference\u201d.<ref name=\"HabibSociety\">Habib, Hala. \"Lydia Canaan: A Star is Born to ''The Sound of Love''\", ''Society'', No. 3, Beirut, February 1997.</ref>\n\nCanaan was the first [[Middle Eastern music#Popular music|Middle Eastern]] artist to sing solely in English,<ref name=\"billboarddec27\"/> and the first to have music videos played on [[MTV Europe]], [[MTV Southeast Asia]], [[MTV Russia]], and [[MTV Middle East]].<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\">Jubayli, Jinan. \"'Angel' Canaan Brings it All Back Home\", ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', No. 10,735, Beirut, March 18, 2002.</ref><ref>Khonji, Tariq. \"Lebanese Singer to Entertain Golf Fans\", ''[[Gulf Daily News]]'', No. 217, Bahrain, October 23, 2001.</ref><ref>\"The MTV Spirit in the Air of Beirut\", ''Magazine'', Beirut, May 19, 1995.</ref> Her musical debut was described as having defied tradition,<ref name=\"Pulse8press\">Pulse-8 Records Press Release, January 1995</ref> challenged [[Convention (norm)|convention]],<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> and transcended millennia-old gender barriers.<ref name=\"HighArabian\">High, Claire. \"With Her Debut Album, ''The Sound of Love'', Recorded in English, Lebanese Singer Lydia Canaan is Tipped to Be the First Middle-Eastern Female Singer to Break into the International Market\", ''Arabian Woman'', No. 21, Saudi Arabia, September 2000.</ref> According to ''Arabian Woman'', \u201cas a girl who grew up in the midst of a bloody civil war, Canaan was breaking down seemingly insurmountable barriers&nbsp;... She rocked the establishment\u201d.<ref name=\"HighArabian\"/> In 2015, Canaan was cataloged in the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum's [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame#Library and archives|Library and Archives]].<ref name=\"rock hall\">[http://catalog.rockhall.com/catalog/RG-0009/ref707 \"Library and Archives Subject File (Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum Records\u2014Curatorial Affairs Division Records): Canaan, Lydia, 2015\"]. ''Rock and Roll Hall of Fame Library and Archives''. January 28, 2016. Retrieved January 24, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\n\n=== Early life and education ===\n[[File:Lydia Canaan, Early Life on Mt. Lebanon.jpg|thumb|right|Lydia Canaan, age 8, [[Brummana]], [[Mount Lebanon]], Lebanon]]\nBorn and raised in [[Brummana]], Lebanon during the Lebanese Civil War to a prominent [[Greek Orthodox Christianity in Lebanon#Notable Lebanese Greek Orthodox Christians|Greek Orthodox Christian]] family, Canaan studied at [[Brummana High School#Notable alumni|Brummana High School]] (BHS)<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\"/> and later at [[Lebanese American University]] (LAU).<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\"/>\n\nFrom a young age singing, lyrical composition, and dancing served as an [[Art therapy|outlet]] and [[catharsis]] for Canaan.<ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\"/> At the age of eight, she was awarded the first place prize (in a contest in which all grades competed against each other) by her French elementary school, College des Saints-Coeurs, Bikfaya, for a poem she composed about a child who wept for being scolded for trivial matters such as staining her fingers with ink when she writes.<ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\">Livingstone, David. \"A Beautiful Life; Or, How a Local Girl Ended Up With a Recording Contract in the UK and Who Has Ambitions in the U.S.\", ''Campus'', No. 8, Beirut, February 1997.</ref><ref name=\"Asharq\"/>\n\nRaised in a conservative family,<ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\"/><ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/> Canaan's parents discouraged her from singing [[Rock Music|rock music]] and forbid her to have a [[Music education|musical education]] or [[Vocal pedagogy|formal training]].<ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/> Nevertheless, Canaan cultivated the ability to compose and store melodies and English lyrics by memory alone.<ref name=\"Pulse8press\"/><ref name=\"Asharq\">\"Lydia Canaan, A Lebanese Spreading the Sweet Scent of Her Song in Europe\", ''Asharq'', No. 13,855, Beirut, July 7, 1995.</ref>\n\nAs reported by the newspaper ''Campus'', \u201cFor Lydia Canaan's first gig, she had to throw her trademark short rockish black leather skirt and studs out of her bedroom window in Brummana, put on a long skirt, lie to her conservative father about where she was going, and, after changing into her leather gear, singing her teenage heart out as Angel with the band Equation\u201d.<ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/>\n\n=== Early career ===\n[[File:Canaan performing as Angel at Mont La Salle Theater, Beirut, Lebanon, 1984.jpg|thumb|right|Lydia Canaan performing as Angel at Mont La Salle Theater, [[Beirut]], Lebanon, 1984]]\nIn 1984, the teenaged Canaan\u2014under the stage name ''Angel''\u2014joined the [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]] band Equation,<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\"/> who until then had been intent on finding a male lead singer. Canaan's talent, personality, and stage presence gained her [[List of Lebanese people#Singers, composers, and musicians|national popularity]] among [[Music of Lebanon#Influence of international popular music in Lebanon|Lebanese youth]].<ref name=\"books.google.com.lb\"/><ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> The same year, she donned what would become her trademark, trend-setting look: revealing, studded leather outfits with dramatic capes and hip-length blonde-streaked hair.<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/><ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/> Off stage, Canaan's Alma Mater, [[Brummana High School]] (BHS), voted her \u201cBest Dressed\u201d. On stage, her provocative costumes contributed to the perception of her as a [[sex symbol]].<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/><ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/> ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'' wrote: \u201cOn stage, with her daring looks and style, Canaan became a role model\u201d.<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> At the height of their success the band drew a crowd of over 15,000.<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\"/> Canaan's first original composition, \u201cWhy All The Hurt\u201d, a tribute to a deceased friend that she wrote as a teenager, was a No. 1 hit on the radio charts in Lebanon.<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/>\n\nFollowing Canaan's first concert with Equation, a ''[[The Gulf Today]]'' writer noted, \u201cthe first show produced a phenomenal reaction . . . It is incredible that amidst the state of civil war that existed in Lebanon at that time, when most people had no idea if they would see another day, she managed to keep her ambitions alive\u201d.<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\"/> ''Society'' magazine stated, \u201ctickets were sold out but more teenagers stormed in to see the young Angel perform... To accommodate the crowd, the concert organizers had to stamp on each fan's hand as they ran out of tickets. It was... \u0570er first success\u201d.<ref name=\"HabibSociety\"/>\n\nCanaan was hailed by the media as the [[List of women's firsts#Other|first]] \u201crock star\u201d of the Middle East.<ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\"/><ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\"/><ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/><ref name=\"Cedar Wings\">Ajouz, Wafik. \"From Broumana to the Top Ten: Lydia Canaan, Lebanon's 'Angel' on the Road to Stardom\", ''Cedar Wings'', No. 28, p. 2, Beirut, July\u2013August 1995.</ref><ref name=\"Eco\">Aschkar, Youmna. \"New Hit For Lydia Canaan\", ''Eco News'', No. 77, p. 2, Beirut, January 20, 1997.</ref> Since her first public appearance, Canaan held over 25 sell-out concerts in the country from 1984\u20131988, and despite the risks and dangers of [[warring]] [[militias]] and armies, recorded her songs for radio, and topped the charts in Lebanon.<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> Her last concert with Equation was held in 1986.<ref name=\"books.google.com.lb\"/>\n\n=== Solo career ===\n[[File:Lydia Canaan MTVE Beirut Lebanon.jpg|thumbnail|Lydia Canaan, [[MTV Europe]] concert, 2000]]\nIn 1987, Canaan embarked on a [[Culture of Lebanon#Music|solo career]],<ref name=\"books.google.com.lb\"/> performing her original compositions, such as \u201cTo Oblivion and Back\u201d, \u201cDoes it Need Some Action\u201d, \u201cA Hard Situation\u201d, \u201cHey Richie\u201d, and \u201cThe Christmas Wish\u201d, all which were radio hits.<ref name=\"Sudha Chandran\"/>\n\nAs Canaan's [[music]] evolved, her fame grew.<ref name=\"books.google.com.lb\"/><ref name=\"HabibSociety\"/> With Lebanon under [[Syrian]] [[Military occupation|occupation]], Canaan's concerts were held in [[East Beirut]], Mount Lebanon, and the north of Lebanon. In [[Tripoli]], the second largest city in Lebanon, Canaan performed in front of a sold-out crowd under tight security despite having received [[death threats]].<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/><ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\"/>\n\nIn 1987, Canaan performed to a crowd of 20,000 at the [[Beirut Rock Festival]].<ref name=\"2U2C\">[http://www.2u2c.com/events/rock/angel-lydia-canaan \"Angel (Lydia Canaan): Beirut Rock Festival 1987\u20131988\"]. ''2U2C''. January 26, 20I7. Retrieved February 3, 2017.</ref> In 1988, she held sell-out concerts for three consecutive nights at [[Casino du Liban]],<ref name=\"Khalife2000\"/><ref name=\"CasinoDuLibanLive\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=v-_tDmJ3-TE Lydia Canaan Live in Concert at Casino du Liban (1988)]. ''[[YouTube]]''. December 23, 2017. Retrieved December 29, 2017.</ref> the last performer to grace its stage until it resumed activity following the end of the [[Michel Aoun#Liberation war against Syria|Liberation War]] in 1990.<ref name=\"Khalife2000\"/>\n\n=== International success ===\nCanaan's international breakthrough was widely reported on by the [[Arab]] media,<ref name=\"HayekNo12513\"/><ref name=\"Khalife2000\"/><ref>Hayek, George. \"Lydia Canaan: 'President Mandela is a Fan of My Music'\", ''An-Nahar'', No. 211, Beirut, February 20, 1997.</ref><ref>Al-Diri, Hanadi. \"Meeting With President and CEO of MTV Networks and the Singer Lydia Canaan\", ''An-Nahar'', Beirut, May 19, 1995.</ref><ref>Hayek, George. \"Lydia Canaan: 'I Will Launch My International Career From the United States'\", ''An-Nahar'', No. 391, Beirut, July 28, 2000.</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Haddad, Viviane. \"Lydia Canaan Shows Readiness to Hold Charity Concerts\u2014The Only Lebanese Singer Who Performs in English and Has Toured the Major European Capitals\", ''Asharq Al-Awsat'', Vol. 24, No. 8,477, London, February 12, 2002.</ref> ''[[Al-Hayat]]'' writing that she had \u201c&nbsp;... invaded the European market with her ballads\u201d.<ref name=\"HayekNo12513\"/> In 1989, she left Lebanon and settled in [[Zurich, Switzerland]],<ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/> where she became a naturalized [[List of Lebanese people in Switzerland#Music|Swiss citizen]].<ref name=\"HighArabian\"/> There she took vocal lessons with soprano Anita Monti.<ref name=\"LivingstoneP1\"/> In 1990, she was interviewed by Radio Z in Zurich, where her songs received airplay.<ref name=\"HighArabian\"/>\n\nIn 1991, Canaan began working with record producer [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]<ref name=\"HabibSociety\"/> (producer of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] and [[David Bowie]]).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perrone|first1=Pierre|title=David Richards: Producer, engineer and musician at Montreux\u2019s Mountain Studios who worked with Bowie, Queen and Duran Duran|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/david-richards-producer-engineer-and-musician-at-montreux-s-mountain-studios-who-worked-with-bowie-9204852.html|accessdate=27 August 2017|work=The Independent|date=20 March 2014}}</ref> The same year, she gave a live interview for [[NBC Europe]].<ref name=\"HayekNo12513\"/> Also in 1991, Canaan signed a two-year contract with London-based production company Spinny Music (led by Queen manager [[Jim Beach]]) to write and record her original songs \u201cShine\u201d,<ref name=\"ShineOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dRMvJUtJ2Tc \u201cShine\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 11, 2016. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> \u201cNever Set You Free\u201d,<ref name=\"NeverSetYouFreeOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fcpUNqOnkJY \u201cNever Set You Free\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 11, 2016. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> \u201cSo Much to Give\u201d,<ref name=\"SoMuchToGiveOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4nmhMDtP8UI \u201cSo Much to Give\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 11, 2016. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> \u201cDesire\u201d,<ref name=\"DesireOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5MDOwUAPT1E \u201cDesire\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. January 21, 2017. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> \u201cLove\u201d,<ref name=\"LoveOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=fDgXUhiFMxg \u201cLove\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 11, 2016. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> and a cover of [[Shirley Bassey]]\u2019s English version of \u201c[[Grande grande grande#Cover versions|Never Never Never]]\u201d,<ref name=\"NeverNeverNeverOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JtdDuOWY-2A \u201cNever Never Never\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. January 25, 2017. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> produced by David Richards at [[Mountain Studios]] in [[Montreux]], Switzerland.<ref name=\"HabibSociety\"/> The same year, she recorded the duet \u201cLove and Lust\u201d with Queen drummer [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]].<ref name=\"Ultimate Queen\">[http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/roger-taylor/songs/collaborations-2.htm \"Roger Taylor Collaborations\"]. ''Ultimate Queen''. May 8, 2016. Retrieved January 24, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"Queen Vault\">[http://www.queenvault.com/rogerplus.html \"Roger Plus\"]. ''Queen Vault''. June 10, 2016. Retrieved January 24, 2017.</ref>\n\nIn 1993, Canaan recorded songs \u201c[[Libnan (Lydia Canaan song)|Libnan]]\u201d,<ref name=\"LibnanOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ImbzskCyork \u201cLibnan\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 11, 2016. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> \u201cFallin'\u201d,<ref name=\"Fallin'OfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UdY44NKHP8s \u201cFallin'\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 11, 2016. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref> and her cover of [[John Lennon]]\u2019s \u201c[[Gimme Some Truth#Cover versions and performances by other artists|Gimme Some Truth]]\u201d.<ref name=\"GimmeSomeTruthOfficialAudio\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0yCE2VkJ3Dg \u201cGimme Some Truth\u201d Official Audio]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 11, 2016. Retrieved October 25, 2017.</ref>\n\n=== Transition to pop ===\n==== \"Beautiful Life\" ====\n{{main | Beautiful Life (Lydia Canaan song)}}\nIn February 1995, Canaan, who had up until that time performed rock under the stage name Angel, dropped the [[moniker]], and under her [[legal name|birth name]] Lydia Canaan presented the pop ballad \u201c[[Beautiful Life (Lydia Canaan song)|Beautiful Life]]\u201d<ref name=\"Discogs\">[https://www.discogs.com/Lydia-Canaan-Beautiful-Life/master/581700 \"Lydia Canaan \u2013 Beautiful Life\"]. ''Discogs''. January 25, 20I7. Retrieved February 3, 2017.</ref> (produced by [[Barry Blue]] and [[The Rapino Brothers]])<ref name=\"Russ Kane\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S_TcORRLuRU Lydia Canaan \u2013 Russ Kane interview (1995)]. ''[[YouTube]]''. February 26, 2017. Retrieved February 26, 2017.</ref> at the [[Midem]] in [[Cannes]], France.<ref>\"Cannes Bye Bye Day\", ''Midem Daily News'', No. 5, Cannes, February 3, 1995.</ref> That Spring, Canaan's international release of the single \u201cBeautiful Life\u201d<ref name=\"Discogs\"/> by London-based Pulse-8 Records<ref name=\"Discogs\"/> gained her international critical acclaim,<ref name=\"books.google.com.lb\"/><ref>Robinson, Nick. \"Lydia Canaan: Beautiful Life\", ''[[Music Week]]'', London, May 13, 1995.</ref><ref name=\"MusicMonitor\">Sexton, Paul. \"New Artist File\", ''Music Monitor'', London, April 21, 1995.</ref> the buzz culminating in a promo tour in England and radio airplay in the UK, Europe, South Africa, and the Middle East.<ref name=\"MusicMonitor\"/>\n\nCanaan performed \u201cBeautiful Life\u201d at the launch of MTV Europe held in [[Beirut]] on May 12, 1995.<ref>Homan, Tim. \"MTV's Arabic Show Breaks Into Beirut\", ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', https://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2000/Aug-01/31887-mtvs-arabic-show-breaks-into-beirut.ashx, Beirut, August 1, 2000.</ref><ref name=\"DanielMTVpress\">Daniel, Judith. MTV Europe press release, Beirut, May 12, 1995.</ref><ref name=\"BlitzPressRelease\">\u201cBlitz Press Release\u201d, Beirut, May 12, 1995.</ref> In promoting the event, MTV Europe billed her as \u201cthe diva from the Middle East\u201d.<ref name=\"DanielMTVpress\"/> During the press conference, President of MTV Europe Peter Einstein stated, \u201cMTV is proud and privileged to play Lydia's videos on Music-Non-Stop Show&nbsp;... All at MTV have fallen in love with Lydia, her songs, and her performance.\u201d<ref name=\"BlitzPressRelease\"/>\n\n==== \"Guardian Angel\" ====\nIn early 2000, \u201cGuardian Angel\u201d, Canaan\u2019s duet with [[Robin Scott (singer)|Robin Scott]],<ref name=\"Discog\">[http://www.discog.info/M-tracklist.html \"M Tracklist: An alphabetical list of all 'M' & Robin Scott songs & versions.\"]. ''Discog.Info''. January 28, 2010. Retrieved January 24, 2017.</ref> appeared on [[M (band)|M]]'s album ''Famous Last Words'', released by [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG Music]].<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/album/release/famous-last-words-mr0004687059 Lydia Canaan \u201cGuardian Angel\u201d track credit] ''All Music''. November 2, 2017. Retrieved December 4, 2017.</ref>\n\n==== \"The Sound of Love\" ====\nCanaan's second single, \u201cThe Sound of Love\u201d,<ref name=\"Maison Rouge Studios\">{{cite web|last1=Harris|first1=Tony|title=Maison Rouge Studios|url=http://www.philsbook.com/maison-rouge.html|publisher=Classic UK Studios|accessdate=3 February 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140308194223/http://www.philsbook.com/maison-rouge.html|archivedate=March 8, 2014}}</ref> produced by Barry Blue and The Rapino Brothers<ref name=\"Russ Kane\"/> and recorded at the Maison Rouge Studios in London,<ref name=\"Maison Rouge Studios\"/> was released in 1997. In 1998, Canaan's recordings, made in New York City at Jay Ward's Dogbrain Music, were exhibited on billboardtalentnet.com, a web site promoting unsigned talent, and appeared on its RadioBTN top 10 chart.<ref name=\"Mw0EAAAAMBAJ p 50\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=Mw0EAAAAMBAJ ''Billboard TalentNet RadioBTN Top 50''], p. 30, New York, December 25, 1998.</ref>\n\nCanaan's debut studio album, ''The Sound of Love'',<ref name=\"Discogs Sound of Love album\">[http://www.discogs.com/Lydia-Canaan-The-Sound-Of-Love/release/3141152 \"Lydia Canaan discography \u2013 ''The Sound of Love'' release\"]. ''Discogs''. December 21, 20I2. Retrieved February 5, 2017.</ref> was released in the summer of 2000. Recorded in London and New York City and including the track \u201cRight on the Verge\u201d, featuring [[Tommy Mandel]].<ref name=\"Discogs Sound of Love album\"/><ref name=\"Tommy Mandel\">[http://www.tommymandel.com/NewTom.html \"New Tom\"]. ''Tommy Mandel''. December 31, 2009. Retrieved January 24, 2017.</ref> The album was distributed by SIDI/XEMA in [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Kuwait]], [[UAE]], [[Bahrain]], [[Qatar]], [[Oman]], [[Egypt]], [[Jordan]], and Lebanon.<ref name=\"Discogs Sound of Love album\"/> In support of the album release, Canaan performed various venues in [[Beirut]], Jumeira Beach Hotel in [[Dubai]], and Savage Garden Club<ref>Lebanese Pop Star Set to Rock Savage Garden\", ''[[Gulf Daily News]]'', Vol. XXIV, No. 198, Bahrain, October 4, 2001.</ref> and Rifaa Golf Club in [[Manama, Bahrain]].<ref name=\"GDN10262001\">\"Charity Golf Drive Opens\", ''[[Gulf Daily News]]'', Vol. XXIV, No. 220, Bahrain, October 26, 2001.</ref>\n\n==== \"Libnan\" ====\n{{main | Libnan (Lydia Canaan song)}}\nIn 2004, \u201cLibnan\u201d was chosen as the title song of the advertisement \u201cRediscover Lebanon\u201d, produced and broadcast by [[CNN]] and commissioned by the Lebanese Ministry of Economy & Trade to promote Lebanon as a tourist destination.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lebanese Economy and Trade Ministry launches landmark campaign on CNN|url=http://www.ameinfo.com/news/Detailed/37849.html|accessdate=4 October 2017|work=AME Info|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050215135524/http://www.ameinfo.com/news/Detailed/37849.html|archivedate=February 15, 2005}}</ref><ref>\nEl Zein, Tarek. [http://www.dailystar.com.lb/Business/Lebanon/2004/Apr-16/682-year-long-advertising-campaign-promotes-lebanon-as-a-global-tourist-destination.ashx \"Year-Long Advertising Campaign Promotes Lebanon as a Global Tourist Destination\"], ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', Beirut, April 16, 2004. Retrieved May 1, 2017.</ref>\n\n==== \"Never Set You Free\" ====\nIn 2014, Canaan was named a semi-finalist by the UK Songwriting Contest for her song \u201cNever Set You Free\u201d.<ref name=\"UK Contest\">[http://www.songwritingcontest.co.uk/2014-results.html \"UK Songwriting Contest 2014 Results\"]. ''UK Songwriting Contest''. September 9, 2016. Retrieved August 18, 2017.</ref>\n\n== Activism and humanitarian work ==\n\n=== Activism ===\n[[File:Lydia Canaan UN HRC.jpg|thumb|right|Lydia Canaan delivering a speech at the 26th Session of the United Nations Human\nRights Council at the [[Palais des Nations]], [[Geneva]], Switzerland, 2014]]\nIn 2014, Canaan was compelled toward activism as a [[United Nations|United Nations delegate]]<ref name=\"HuffPo Fighting Terrorism\">Canaan, Lydia. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lydia-canaan/fighting-terrorism-withou_b_9513034.html \"Fighting Terrorism Without Violating Human Rights\"]. ''[[HuffPost]]''. March 21, 2016. Retrieved February 27, 2017.</ref><ref name=\"HuffPo Islamophobia\">Canaan, Lydia. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lydia-canaan/islamophobia-and-art_b_13931724.html \"Islamophobia and Art\"]. ''[[HuffPost]]''. January 2, 2017. Retrieved February 27, 2017.</ref> for Khiam Rehabilitation Center for Victims of Torture (KRC) to the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] ([[UNHRC]]).<ref name=\"khiamcenter.org\">[http://www.khiamcenter.org/en/ \"Khiam Rehabilitation Center for Victims of Torture (KRC)\"]. ''Khiam Rehabilitation Center for Victims of Torture''. April 14, 2016. Retrieved February 5, 2017.</ref>\n\n* On March 17, 2014, Canaan delivered her speech, \u201cIslamophobia and Art\u201d, about the need to combat [[Islamophobia|anti-Muslim prejudice]] artistically, at the 25th Session of the United Nations Human Rights Council at the [[Palace of Nations, Geneva|Palais des Nations]] in [[Geneva]], Switzerland, gaining a round of applause and kudos.<ref name=\"HuffPo Islamophobia\"/>\n* On June 17, 2014, Canaan delivered her speech, \u201cHostage to Injustice\u201d, a call for an end to unjust [[Political prisoner|political imprisonment]], at the 26th Session of the United Nations Human Rights Council at the Palais des Nations in Geneva, Switzerland, receiving a standing ovation and drawing media attention.<ref name=\"Hostage\">Canaan, Lydia. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lydia-canaan/hostage-to-injustice_b_14232106.html \"Hostage to Injustice\"], ''[[HuffPost]]''. June 17, 2014. Retrieved February 27, 2017.</ref>\n* On March 13, 2015, Canaan delivered her speech, \u201cHumane Evolution\u201d, in which she spoke out against sanctioned [[torture]], at the 28th Session of the United Nations Human Rights Council at the Palais des Nations in Geneva, Switzerland, winning her extended applause.<ref name=\"Humane Evolution\">Canaan, Lydia. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/lydia-canaan/humane-evolution_b_14419716.html \"Humane Evolution\"], ''[[HuffPost]]'', February 1, 2017. Retrieved February 1, 2017.</ref>\n* On November 3, 2015, Canaan delivered a speech condemning governments worldwide for failure to implement UN human rights recommendations at the UNHRC's 23rd Session of the [[Universal Periodic Review|Universal Periodic Review (UPR)]], attended by over twenty-five delegations and representatives from Great Britain, Germany, Norway, France, the European Union, Denmark, Australia, Ireland, and Lebanon, among others at the Palais des Nations in Geneva, Switzerland. She also sang an a cappella verse of her activist anthem \u201cHumanity Wake Up and Fight\u201d.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I2r9iXgyt_E \"Humanity Wake Up and Fight\"]. ''[[YouTube]]''. March 22, 2016. Retrieved February 26, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://nna-leb.gov.lb/ar/show-news/188896/#.Vjs3Kmmi6VY.facebook \"The Lebanese Report Before the United Nations Human Rights Council that Included Failure to Act Upon Recommendations as Pledged\"]. ''National News Agency (NNA)''. November 8, 2015. Retrieved February 27, 2017.</ref><ref>[http://www.khiamcenter.org/upr Khiam Rehabilitation Center (KRC), UNHRC-UPR, November 3, 2015]. ''Khiam Center''. March 18, 2016. Retrieved February 26, 2017.</ref>\n* On March 18, 2016, Canaan delivered \u201cFighting Terrorism Without Violating Human Rights\u201d,<ref name=\"HuffPo Fighting Terrorism\"/> her impassioned speech in defense of innocent civilian victims of [[counter-terrorism]], at the 31st Session of the United Nations Human Rights Council (UNHRC) at the Palais des Nations in Geneva, Switzerland. It was streamed live on [[YouTube]] by the Universal Periodic Review (UPR).<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hD8r98ahDTs \"Fighting Terrorism Without Violating Human Rights\"]. ''[[YouTube]]''. March 18, 2016. Retrieved February 27, 2017.</ref>\n* On March 14, 2017, Canaan delivered her speech titled \u201cGlobal Effects of the Persecution of Religious Minorities in the Middle East\u201d,<ref name=\"Religious Minorities\">Canaan, Lydia. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/global-effects-of-the-persecution-of-religious-minorities_us_58e95b89e4b00dd8e016ec90 \u201cGlobal Effects of the Persecution of Religious Minorities in the Middle East\"], ''[[HuffPost]]'', April 8, 2017. Retrieved April 9, 2017.</ref> which primarily focused on the persecution of Christians (who, according to her speech, are the most persecuted [[Minority religion|religious minority]] in the Middle East and the world), at the 34th Session of the United Nations Human Rights Council (UNHRC) at the Palais des Nations in Geneva, Switzerland; her emotional delivery ended with Canaan in tears.<ref name=\"Global Effects Video\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=o0QYPpL5dl8 \u201cGlobal Effects of the Persecution of Religious Minorities in the Middle East\"]. ''[[YouTube]]''. March 30, 2017. Retrieved February 27, 2017.</ref>\n\n=== Humanitarian work ===\n[[File:Lydiacanaanhumanitarian.jpg|thumb|right|Lydia Canaan speaking to a [[Palestinian territories|Palestinian]] man at the Social Support Society Active Ageing House refugee camp, Burj Al-Barajneh, [[Beirut]], Lebanon, 2011]]\n* In 2001, Canaan performed at the United Nations International Volunteers Day in [[Beirut]]<ref name=\"UNDP Lebanon\">[http://www.undp.org.lb/partners/privatesector/ivd2001/index.cfm The Celebration of the International Volunteer Day (IVD) and the Wrap Up of IYV2001 in Lebanon]. ''UNDP Lebanon''. February 17, 2017. Retrieved February 26, 2017.</ref> and was awarded for her humanitarianism by Yves de San, Head of [[UNDP]] Lebanon.<ref name=\"UNDP Lebanon\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n* In 2014, Canaan participated in the Arab International Forum in Solidarity With Palestinian Prisoners, held in Beirut, Lebanon, with over three hundred fifty public figures and other international attendees, headed by former U.S. Attorney General [[Ramsey Clark]].<ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\"/>\n* In 2015, Canaan took part in the International Forum for Justice in Palestine, held in Beirut, Lebanon, with over five hundred attendees from the U.S., Europe, and the Middle East, headed by former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark.<ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\"/>\n\nCanaan supports [[Solitary Watch]], [[John Legend]]'s Free America campaign,<ref>[http://www.letsfreeamerica.org/ #FreeAmerica]. ''Let's Free America''. July 6, 2016. Retrieved February 26, 2017.</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]], [[War Child (charity)|War Child Holland-Lebanon]], SAWA for DEV & AID, and the International Campaign to Prosecute War Crimes in Iraq chaired by former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark.<ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\"/>\n\n=== Charity work ===\n[[File:Lydiacanaancharitable.jpg|thumb|right|Lydia Canaan singing with a [[Palestinian territories|Palestinian]] woman at the Social Support Society Active Ageing House refugee camp, Burj Al-Barajneh, [[Beirut]], Lebanon, 2011]]\nThroughout her life, Canaan has donated her money, music, and time to many charities,<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> particularly those concerned with children, animals, and the elderly.<ref name=\"Daily Star Rock Hall\"/><ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\"/><ref name=\"animal welfare support\"/><ref name=\"thank you\"/> She reportedly made generous donations to the Children's Care Unit of Salmaniyah Hospital,<ref name=\"GDN10262001\"/> [[Child Fund|Child Fund International]] (CFI), and [[St. Jude's Hospital]], and has performed at charity and fundraiser events including American Women's Club,<ref name=\"thank you\">Bechara, June. \"Letter of Thanks\", American Women's Club, Beirut, May 19, 2001.</ref> Salmaniyah Hospital (Children's Care Unit),<ref name=\"GDN10262001\"/> Beirut [[Rotary Club]], [[American Community School at Beirut|American Community School]],<ref>Rawas, Nada. \"PC Annual Dinner: Great Success\", ''ACS Newsletter'', Vol. III, No. 7, Beirut, April 2001.</ref> Association pour la Promotion Feminine,<ref name=\"Mondanite, No. 75, April 2003\">\"Association To Promote Women\", ''Mondanite'', No. 75, Beirut, April 2003.</ref><ref>\"Fundraiser Dinner For Women at Phoenicia\", ''Snob'', No. 105, Beirut, April, 2003.</ref> Caritas Internationalis (Liban),<ref name=\"Caritas Info\">\"A Gala Dinner In Support Of Caritas Medical Action\", ''Caritas Info'', Beirut, March 2005.</ref> Centre Renee Wehbe Le Vieillard Malade, Beirut for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (BETA),<ref name=\"defending animal welfare\"/> [[Lion's Club|Lion's Beirut Code Club]],<ref>\"Inauguration of Lions Club Beirut Code\", ''Albalad'', No. 747, Beirut, February 8, 2011.</ref> Unite Lebanon Youth Project (ULYP),<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> Arab Resource Center for Popular Arts, Al-Jana (ARCPA),<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> Social Support Society Active Ageing House,<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/> NASMA Foundation,<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/> and Association Amour et Partage.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\nHer song, \u201c[[Beautiful Life (Lydia Canaan song)|Beautiful Life]]\u201d, was selected by South African President [[Nelson Mandela]] as the theme song for a charity event in South Africa.<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Ali, Avishka. \"Lydia in Love With Bahrain\", ''Bahrain This Month'', No. 51, Bahrain, November 2001.</ref><ref name=\"ACSvol3no5\">\"ACS Speaker of the Month Program Welcomes Singer Lydia Canaan\", ''ACS Newsletter'', Vol. III, No. 5, Beirut, February 2001.</ref><ref name=DailyStarFebruary152002>[http://www.dailystar.com.lb/News/Lebanon-News/2002/Feb-15/109434-news-in-brief-published-on-15022002.ashx \"Pop Star Brings 'Beautiful Life' to Baabda Palace\"], ''[[The Daily Star (Lebanon)|The Daily Star]]'', No. 10,711, Beirut, February 15, 2002.</ref>\n\n=== Advocacy ===\n[[File:Lydia Canaan at MY World Partners Awards Ceremony.jpeg|thumbnail|Lydia Canaan at the [[United Nations]] MY World partners awards ceremony, [[United Nations|UN]] Headquarters, [[New York City]], 2014]]\n\n* In 2015, Canaan performed at a rally in solidarity with Cardinal Patriarch [[Bechara Boutros Al-Rahi]]'s call to elect a president of the [[Republic of Lebanon]] at [[Saint George Maronite Cathedral, Beirut|St. George Cathedral]] in Beirut.<ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\"/>\n\n=== Support for animal welfare ===\nCanaan, an outspoken [[animal welfare|animal welfare supporter]]<ref name=\"animal welfare support\">\"Thank You To Our Dear Supporters\", BETA (Beirut for the Ethical Treatment of Animals), ''The Beta Team Letter'', Beirut, November, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"defending animal welfare\">\"A Gala Dinner To Defend Animal Welfare Cause\", ''Mondanite'', No. 141, Beirut, November 2008.</ref><ref name=\"best friend\">\"For Man's Best Friend\", ''Femme Magazine'', No. 187, Beirut, November, 2008.</ref> and [[List of animal rights advocates|animal rights activist]],<ref name=\"animal welfare support\"/><ref name=\"defending animal welfare\"/><ref name=\"best friend\"/> supports the Asian Conservation Awareness Programme (ACAP/WildAid), the [[World Wildlife Fund]] (WWF), Le Roselet Foundation, and Beirut for the Ethical Treatment of Animals (BETA).<ref name=\"animal welfare support\"/>\n\n=== Public speaking ===\n\n* In 2001, Canaan was invited as Speaker of the Month by American Community School (ACS) in Beirut, Lebanon.<ref name=\"ACSvol3no5\"/>\n* Canaan delivered the speech \u201cIt's About Time, My Country\u201d in support of the [[Lebanese Armed Forces]] on Independence Day 2014 at [[Casino du Liban]] in Beirut, Lebanon.<ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\"/>\n\n== Film and literature ==\n\n=== Film ===\n\nIn 2014, Canaan was interviewed by America-based Global Sorority Foundation for their documentary film series as a [[List of women's rights activists#Lebanon|prime example]] for young girls worldwide to overcome adversity and raise awareness for [[gender equality]].<ref name=\"globalsorority.com\">Kelly, Tia. [http://www.globalsorority.com/back_from_beirut_global_sorority_works_in_the_middle_east_for_the_first_time?recruiter_id=2 \"Back from Beirut\"], ''Global Sorority'', San Diego, November 20, 2014.</ref>\n\n=== Literature ===\nAmerican author Robert W. McGee mentioned Canaan's songs \u201cSo Much To Give\u201d and \u201cNever Set You Free\u201d in his two novels ''Justifiable Homicide'' (2014)<ref name=\"Justifiable\">McGee, Robert W. (2014). [https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00OJMWLK2 ''Justifiable Homicide''], Fayetteville. {{ISBN|978-1-5028-6213-6}}.</ref> and ''Annie and the Senator'' (2015);<ref name=\"Annie\">McGee, Robert W. (2015). [https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00TKOTORC ''Annie and the Senator''], Fayetteville.</ref> Canaan and her songs \u201cShine\u201d, \u201cFallin'\u201d, and \u201c[[Libnan (Lydia Canaan song)|Libnan]]\u201d were referenced in all three volumes of McGee's ''The Iraqi Girl Trilogy'' (2015).<ref name=\"Trilogy1\">McGee, Robert W. (2015). [https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0188LDU5O ''The Iraqi Girl: Trilogy Book 1''], Fayetteville.</ref><ref name=Trilogy2>McGee, Robert W. (2015). [https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0188M7EGY ''The Iraqi Girl: Trilogy Book 2''], Fayetteville.</ref>  McGee's [[Character (arts)|characters]] often risk their lives to listen to Lydia Canaan's music.<ref name=\"Justifiable\"/><ref name=\"Trilogy1\"/><ref name=\"Trilogy2\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Canaan was featured in British journalist for ''[[Newsweek]]'' Orlando Crowcroft\u2019s book ''Rock in a Hard Place: Music and Mayhem in the Middle East'', about the dangers she faced and obstacles she overcame as a rock music pioneer in Lebanon.<ref name=HardPlace>Crowcroft, Orlando. (2017). ''Rock in a Hard Place: Music and Mayhem in the Middle East'', London: [[Zed Books]]. {{ISBN|978-1-78699-016-7}}.</ref>\n\n== Honors and awards ==\n\n=== Honors ===\n[[File:Canaan with President Lahoud.jpg|thumb|right|Lydia Canaan with Lebanese President [[Emile Lahoud]] at the [[Baabda Palace|Presidential Palace]], [[Baabda]], Lebanon, 2002]]\n\n* On January 16, 2002, Canaan was received by Lebanese President [[Emile Lahoud]] at the [[Baabda Palace|Presidential Palace]] in [[Baabda]], Lebanon. President [[Emile Lahoud|Lahoud]] thanked Canaan for her devotion to, affection for, and altruistic services rendered to her country.<ref name=\"TDSmarch182002\"/><ref>\"President Emile Lahoud Receiving the International Pop Singer Lydia Canaan at the Presidential Palace\", ''An-Nahar'', No. 21,154, Beirut, January 17, 2002.</ref><ref>\"President Emile Lahoud Meeting With the International Rock Singer Lydia Canaan at the Presidential Palace\", ''Al-Mustaqbal'', Beirut, January 17, 2002.</ref><ref>\"President Emile Lahoud Meeting With International Lebanese Pop Star Lydia Canaan at Presidential Palace\", ''Assafir'', Beirut, January 17, 2002.</ref><ref>\"President Emile Lahoud Meeting With the International Pop Icon Lydia Canaan at the Presidential Palace\", ''Al-Anwar'', Beirut, January 17, 2002.</ref>\n* On January 28, 2002, Canaan was received by First Lady Andree Lahoud at the [[Baabda Palace|Presidential Palace]], who expressed her gratitude and admiration for Canaan for putting a positive cultural and [[artistic]] face on Lebanon.<ref>\"First Lady Lahood Receives Lebanese Pop Singer\", ''Al-Mustaqbal'', No. 890, Beirut, January 29, 2002.</ref><ref>\"First Lady Andree Lahoud to Receive the International Rock Singer Lydia Canaan at the Presidential Palace\", ''An-Nahar'', No. 21,164, Beirut, January 29, 2002.</ref>\n* On February 15, 2002, Canaan was received by the First Lady Andree Lahoud at the [[Baabda Palace|Presidential Palace]], who requested that Canaan hold a concert at the Presidential Palace in honor of the wives of the fallen [[Republican Guard (Lebanon)|Republican Guard]] Officers.<ref>\"The First Lady Invites Artist Lydia Canaan to Perform at the Presidential Palace\", ''Al-Kifah Al-Arabi'', No. 3,109, Beirut, February 15, 2002.</ref><ref>\"First Lady Andree Lahoud Invited Rock Star Lydia Canaan to Perform at the Presidential Palace\", ''An-Nahar'', No. 21,179, February 15, 2002.</ref><ref>\"First Lady Andree Lahoud Invites International Pop Singer Lydia Canaan to Perform at Baabda Palace\", ''Assafir'', No. 9,128, Beirut, February 15, 2002.</ref><ref>\"First Lady of Lebanon Andree Lahoud Invited Lydia Canaan to Perform at Presidential Palace\", ''Ad-Diyar'', No. 4,799, Beirut, February 15, 2002.</ref>\n* On [[Mother's Day]], March 21, 2002, Canaan was received at the Presidential Palace when, upon the request of First Lady Andree Lahoud, she performed for a presidential ceremony in honor of the wives of the fallen [[Republican Guard (Lebanon)|Republican Guard]] Officers.<ref name=\"DailyStarFebruary152002\"/><ref>\"Lydia Canaan Performs at the Presidential Palace\", ''Al-Mustaqbal'', No. 938, Beirut, March 20, 2002.</ref>\n\n=== Awards ===\n[[File:UNDP Award 2001.jpg|thumb|right|alt=United Nations Building(ESCWA), Beirut/Lebanon|Lydia Canaan receiving the International Year of Volunteers Award by the [[United Nations Development Programme]] ([[UNDP]]), 2001]]\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders unsortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Year !! Award !! By \n!{{Abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 1988\n| Scoop d'Or Award\n| ''Scoop'' magazine\n|<ref>Jabra, Stavro. \"Scoop d'Or\", ''Scoop'', No. 51, Beirut, December 1987 \u2013 January 1988.</ref>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 1997\n| Lebanese International Success Award\n| [[Ministry of Tourism (Lebanon)|Lebanese Ministry of Tourism]]\n|<ref name=\"billboarddec27\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2001\n| International Year of Volunteers Award\n| [[United Nations Development Programme]] ([[UNDP]])\n|<ref name=\"UNDP Lebanon\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2003\n| Association pour la Promotion Feminine Award\n| Association pour la Promotion Feminine\n|<ref name=\"Mondanite, No. 75, April 2003\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2005\n| Caritas Award\n| Caritas\n|<ref name=\"Caritas Info\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"|2014\n| [[Lebanese Army]] Award\n| [[Lebanese Armed Forces]]\n|<ref name=\"dailystar.com.lb\"/>\n|-\n|UK Songwriting Contest Semi-finalist Award\n| UK Songwriting Contest\n|<ref name=\"UK Contest\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|2016\n|[[Silver medal|Silver Medal]] for Outstanding Achievement\n|Global Music Awards\n|<ref>[http://www.globalmusicawards.com/Winners-June-2016.html Global Music Awards: Winners\u2014June 2016]. ''Global Music Awards''. January 17, 2017. Retrieved February 26, 2017.</ref>\n|}\n\n== Videography ==\n\n=== Music videos ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders unsortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:5%;\"| Video !! Year !! Details \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''Hey Richie''<ref name=\"HeyRichieVideo\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=K2ioZoJfLmA \"Hey Richie\" Video]. ''[[YouTube]]''. November 9, 2017. Retrieved November 12, 2017.</ref>\n|\n1988\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Broadcast by [[LBCI]] and [[NBC Europe]].<ref name=\"HayekNo12513\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{nowrap|''[[Beautiful Life (Lydia Canaan song)|Beautiful Life]]''}}<ref name=\"Beautiful Life Video\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BOX1h8MfwQc \"Beautiful Life\" Video]. ''[[YouTube]]''. June 27, 2014. Retrieved August 18, 2017.</ref>\n|\n1995\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Filmed at Canalot Studios and [[Syon House]], the castle of the Duke of Northumberland, in [[London, England|London]], England.<ref name=\"Beautiful Life Video\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''The Sound of Love''<ref name=\"The Sound of Love Video\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BL-u0KTi84w \"The Sound of Love\" Video]. ''[[YouTube]]''. June 27, 2014. Retrieved August 18, 2017.</ref>\n|\n1997\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Filmed at the palace of [[Sir Francis Dashwood]] in [[West Wycombe]], England.<ref name=\"The Sound of Love Video\"/>\n|}\n\n=== Concerts ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders unsortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Video !! Year !! Details\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Live in Concert at [[Casino du Liban]]<ref name=\"CasinoDuLibanLive\"/>\n|1988\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Lydia Canaan performing as Angel live in concert at Casino du Liban.<ref name=\"Khalife2000\"/>\n|}\n\n=== Oration ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders unsortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%;\"| Video !! Year !! Details\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''Hostage to Injustice''<ref name=\"Hostage to Injustice\">Footage of Lydia Canaan delivering her speech [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=q7vuXUg88D8 \"Hostage to Injustice\"]. ''[[YouTube]]''. September 2, 2016. Retrieved August 18, 2017.</ref>\n|\n2014\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Footage of the speech Canaan delivered at the 26th Session of the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] ([[UNHRC]]) at the Palais des Nations in [[Geneva, Switzerland]].<ref name=\"Hostage\"/> It has been widely circulated on the Internet.<ref name=\"Hostage to Injustice\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''Fighting Terrorism Without Violating Human Rights''<ref name=\"Fighting Terrorism Without Violating Human Rights\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hD8r98ahDTs \"Fighting Terrorism Without Violating Human Rights\"]. ''[[YouTube]]''. March 19, 2016. Retrieved August 18, 2017.</ref>\n|\n2016\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Footage of the speech Canaan delivered at the 31st Session of the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] ([[UNHRC]]) at the Palais des Nations in [[Geneva, Switzerland]].<ref name=\"HuffPo Fighting Terrorism\"/> It was streamed live on [[YouTube]] by the Universal Periodic Review (UPR).<ref name=\"Fighting Terrorism Without Violating Human Rights\"/>\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''Global Effects of the Persecution of Religious Minorities in the Middle East''<ref name=\"Religious Minorities\"/>\n|\n2017\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|Footage of the speech Canaan delivered at the 34th Session of the [[United Nations Human Rights Council]] ([[UNHRC]]) at the Palais des Nations in [[Geneva, Switzerland]] capturing Canaan's notably emotional delivery.<ref name=\"Global Effects Video\"/>\n|}\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Studio albums ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:10em;\"| Album title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:12em;\" | Album details\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|''The Sound of Love''\n|\n*Released: 2000\n*Label: SIDI/XEMA\n*Format: [[Compact disc|CD]]\n|}\n'''Track listing'''\n{{Track listing\n| title1          = [[Beautiful Life (Lydia Canaan song)|Beautiful Life]]\n| writer1         = [[Barry Blue]] & [[Marco Sabiu]]\n| length1         = 4:17\n\n| title2          = Right On The Verge (Tommy Mandel Mix)\n| writer2         = Noel Cohen & Daryl Hair\n| length2         = 4:37\n\n| title3          = The Sound of Love\n| writer3         = [[Barry Blue]] & [[Marco Sabiu]]\n| length3         = 4:10\n\n| title4          = A Love That Shines\n| writer4         = Noel Cohen & Keith Plex Barnhart\n| length4         = 4:42\n\n| title5          = The Hurt Won't Hurt (No More)\n| writer5         = [[Barry Blue]]\n| length5         = 3:51\n\n| title6          = Every Goodbye Ain't Gone\n| writer6         = Geena Breedlove, Noel Cohen, & Daryl Hair\n| length6         = 4:07\n\n| title7          = Without You\n| writer7         = Sandy Wilbur & [[Keith Barnhart]]\n| length7         = 4:32\n\n| title8          = Somewhere in the Night\n| writer8         = [[Barry Blue]]\n| length8         = 4:24\n\n| title9          = Right On the Verge (Original Mix)\n| writer9         = Noel Cohen & Daryl Hair\n| length9         = 4:28\n\n| title10          = Fade Away\n| writer10         = Noel Cohen & [[Keith Barnhart]]\n| length10         = 4:30\n\n| total_length     = 44:01\n}}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! scope=\"col\"| Year \n! scope=\"col\"| Single title \n! scope=\"col\"| Writer(s) \n! scope=\"col\"| Release \n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 1985 \n| \u201cThe Sound of Equation\u201d \n| Lydia&nbsp;Canaan\n| Radio\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| 1986 \n| \u201cWhy All the Hurt?\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan \n| Radio\n|-\n| \u201cTo Oblivion and Back\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Radio\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"3\"| 1987 \n| \u201cThe Hope Song\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan \n| Radio\n|-\n| \u201cDoes It Need Some Action?\u201d\n| Lydia Canaan\n| Radio\n|-\n| \u201cA Hard Situation\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Radio\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| 1988 \n| \u201cAnd You Call Me\u201d\n| Lydia Canaan \n| Radio\n|-\n| \u201cHey Richie\u201d\n| Lydia Canaan\n| Radio\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"2\"| 1989 \n| \u201cThe Christmas Wish\u201d\n| Lydia Canaan \n| Radio\n|-\n| \u201cMe and Little Andy\u201d  \n| [[Dolly Parton]]\n| Radio\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 1995 \n| \u201c[[Beautiful Life (Lydia Canaan song)|Beautiful Life]]\u201d \n| [[Barry Blue]]\n| Pulse-8 Records\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 1997 \n| \u201cThe Sound of Love\u201d \n| [[Barry Blue]]\n| Pulse-8 Records\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2000 \n| \u201cGuardian Angel\u201d \n| [[Robin Scott (singer)|Robin Scott]]\n| [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG/Metro]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"| 2004 \n| \u201c[[Libnan (Lydia Canaan song)|Libnan]]\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan \n| [[CNN]]\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"6\"| 2014 \n| \u201cShine\u201d\n| Lydia Canaan\n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201cFallin'\u201d (Remix) \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201cLove\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201cSo Much to Give\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201c[[Gimme Some Truth#Cover versions and performances by other artists|Gimme Some Truth]]\u201d \n| [[John Lennon]] \n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201cNever Set You Free\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Internet\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" rowspan=\"6\"| 2017 \n| \u201cDesire\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201c[[Grande grande grande#Cover versions|Never Never Never]]\u201d \n| Alberto Testa & [[Tony Renis]] \n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201cFallin'\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan\n| Internet\n|-\n| \u201cLove is Blind\u201d \n| Lydia Canaan